{"title_page": "Flute Sonata (Poulenc)", "text_new": "The '''''Sonate pour fl\u00fbte et piano''''' ('''Flute Sonata'''), [[FP (Poulenc)|FP]] 164, by [[Francis Poulenc]], for [[flute]] and [[piano]], was written in 1957. It is dedicated to the memory of [[Elizabeth Sprague Coolidge]], an American patron of chamber music.  Poulenc composed it for the flautist [[Jean-Pierre Rampal]], and he and Rampal gave the premi\u00e8re in June 1957 at the [[Strasbourg Music Festival]]. It is now one of Poulenc's best known works and is a prominent feature in 20th-century flute repertoire.\n\n==Background and first performance==\nPoulenc began to think of writing a flute sonata in 1952, but he was occupied with his Sonata for Two Pianos and then his opera, ''[[Dialogues of the Carmelites|Dialogues des Carm\u00e9lites]]''.<ref name=nimbus>Clements, Dominy (2015). Notes to Nimbus CD NI 5933</ref> In April 1956, when he was still working on the opera, he was approached by [[Harold Spivacke]] of the American [[Library of Congress]] with a request to write a piece for two pianos or alternatively a chamber piece for up to six instruments.<ref>Schmidt (2001), p. 408</ref> Poulenc was too busy to accept, but Spivacke persisted. Poulenc told him, \"Much more at home with wind instruments than strings, I admit I am tempted by this combination\",{{refn|Poulenc had always preferred winds \u2013 with their similarities to the human voice \u2013 to stringed instruments: \"nothing could be further from human breath than the stroke of a bow\". He thought little of his own sonatas for cello and for violin.<ref>Mellers, pp. 160\u2013161</ref>|group=n}}            and in August he agreed to go ahead.<ref name=ib>Battioni, Isabelle (2000). Notes to Naxos CD 8.553611</ref> The sonata was commissioned in memory of a musical benefactor, [[Elizabeth Sprague Coolidge]], to whom Poulenc dedicated the work.<ref name=nimbus/> \n\nPoulenc spent the winter of 1956\u201357 in [[Cannes]], where he composed the sonata between December and March.<ref name=mm>Malcolm MacDonald (2013). Notes to Opus Arte CD OACD9012D</ref> When he had completed the first two of the three movements, he wrote to his friend [[Pierre Bernac]]:\n{{blockindent|In working on this Flute Sonata I have the feeling of going back a long way, but with a more settled technique. It's a sonata of [[Claude Debussy|Debussyan]] dimensions. It's the French sense of balance [''la mesure fran\u00e7aise'']. Finding the form for your language is the most difficult thing. It's what [[Anton Webern|Webern]] has in the highest degree \u2026 and what [[Pierre Boulez|Boulez]] has not yet found.<ref>Nichols, p. 251</ref>|}}\n\nOn 18 June 1957, the public premiere was given by the flautist [[Jean-Pierre Rampal]], with the composer at the piano, at the [[Strasbourg Music Festival]].<ref name=hype>Mawer, Deborah (2001). Notes to Hyperion CD CDH55386</ref>{{refn|Rampal and Poulenc had given gave the work a private performance the previous day to an audience of one: the pianist [[Arthur Rubinstein]], who could not be present at the official premiere.<ref name=mm/>|group=n}}\n\n==Music==\nThe sonata is in three movements.The musicologist [[Malcolm MacDonald (music critic)|Malcolm MacDonald]] writes:\n{{block indent|The work is infused with Poulenc\u2019s trademark bittersweet grace, wit, irony and sentiment, which are manifested in different ways in each of its three movements. The first \u2026 makes clear the composer\u2019s elegiac intentions; the second is a haunting cantilena for the flute. Very fast and very tricky for the players, the skittish and vivacious \u2026 finale brings the work to a close in cheerful and sardonic style.<ref name=mm/>}}\n===''Allegretto malincolico''===\nThe movement starts in {{music|time|2|4}} with an opening four-bar phrase with a descending theme, beginning with a broken [[Triad (music)|triad]] of [[Thirty-second note |demisemiquavers]] around high E and declining to the G above [[C  (musical  note)#Middle  C |middle C]]. The piano's right hand part interweaves arpeggiated semiquavers over a [[pedal point|pedal]] in the left hand.<ref name=m156>Mellers, p. 156</ref> This is followed by an upward scale by both flute and piano leading to a contrasting theme, also descending.<ref>Rifkin,  pp. 141\u2013142</ref> The musicologist [[Malcolm MacDonald (music critic)|Malcolm MacDonald]] comments that the opening \"makes clear the composer\u2019s elegiac intentions\", and other analysts write of the \"poignancy\" of the principal theme, despite the seemingly vivacious tempo.<ref name=nimbus/><ref name=mm/><ref name=m163>Mellers, p. 163</ref> A counter-theme in F major gives the flute upwardly-leaping [[arpeggio]]s, before the opening theme returns in A minor. [[Wilfrid Mellers]] comments that the reappearance of the first theme in an unexpected key makes it clear that Poulenc is not following [[sonata form]] but is using \"a subtle ternary structure\".<ref name=m163/> After a slightly faster middle section there is a recapitulation of a kind, with, in Mellers's words \"enharmonic ambiguities that justify the 'malinconico' of the directive\", and:\n\n{{blockindent|Fragments of the first section's airborne melody intermingle with ecstatic spurtings of the middle theme. A coda to the coda is explicitly based on [[blue note|blue]] false relations between major and minor thirds.<ref>Mellers, p. 164</ref>|}}\n\nThe flute part is technically demanding in this movement, with frequent trills and demisemiquaver tonguing.<ref name=hype/>\n===''Cantilena: Assez lent''===\nThis movement is much slower and quieter. It begins with two quavers on the piano, which are echoed by the flute during the course of the next two bars. The haunting tune features minimal decoration, and is accompanied by flowing quavers on the piano. In the middle of the piece, the atmosphere suddenly changes to loud high notes on the flute, reaching a top B. However soon after it returns to the original slow tune. \n\n===''Presto giocoso''===\nThis movement is predominantly loud and fast, and Poulenc's \"trademark motif\" mentioned above reappears in the contrasting central section.\n\n==Later concert performances and recordings==\nPoulenc considered giving the American premiere together with Rampal during a planned US tour, but the tour did not take place and Rampal gave the American premiere in February 1958 with his regular accompanist [[Robert Veyron-Lacroix]].<ref>Schmidt (2002), p. 464</ref> Poulenc was pleased to accompany other flautists in the sonata. In January 1959 he accompanied [[Gareth Morris]] in the British premiere, in an all-Poulenc programme that included the world premiere of his ''\u00c9l\u00e9gie in memory of Dennis Brain'' for horn and piano.<ref>\"[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/1341c32439144c329b0ff1b9569f02d6?page=35 Third Programme]\", ''Radio Times'', 14 February 1959, p. 31</ref> Later in that year Poulenc played the piano part with [[Maxence Larrieu]] in [[Avignon]], Rampal in Paris and [[Christian Lard\u00e9]] in [[Menton]]. in 2015, the pianist and scholar [[David Owen Norris]] called the sonata \"probably the world's most played piece for flute and piano\".<ref name=bal>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sounds/play/p0381qw0 \"Building a Library\"], BBC Radio 3, 14 November 2015. Statement made at 1 minute from start. The survey is reported in the BBC's Music Magazine at [http://www.classical-music.com/article/best-recordings-poulencs-flute-sonata\" The best recordings of Poulenc's Flute Sonata\"], BBC. Retrieved 7 April 2020</ref>\n\n===Recordings===\nThe American premiere was recorded, as was the composer's Paris performance with Rampal.<ref>Car\u00e9, pp. 39\u201340</ref> There have been many subsequent recordings of the sonata. Among the earlier ones are those by [[Michel Debost]] with [[Jacques Fevrier]] and Rampal with Veyron-Lacroix. Later recordings include those by [[Julius Baker]] with Lisa Logan and [[Mathieu Dufour]] with [[\u00c9ric Le Sage]]. Among recordings singled out in a [[BBC Radio 3]] survey in 2015 are those by  [[William Bennett (flautist)|William Bennett]] with Clifford Benson; [[Sharon Bezaly]] with [[Ronald Brautigam]]; [[Patrick Gallois]] with [[Pascal Rog\u00e9]]; [[Emmanuel Pahud]] with Le Sage]; Ileana Ruhemann with [[Kathron Sturrock]]; and [[Adam Walker (flautist)|Adam Walker]] with James Baillieu.<ref name=bal/>\n\n==Orchestral version==\nIn 1976 the flautist [[James Galway]] asked the English composer [[Lennox Berkeley|Sir Lennox Berkeley]], a good friend of Poulenc's for many years, to orchestrate the sonata.<ref name=lb/> While working on it, Berkeley wrote in his diary:\n{{blockindent|The task of orchestrating Poulenc's Flute Sonata ... proves as difficult as I had feared. ... The difficulty is the entirely pianistic nature of the accompaniment, extremely difficult to translate into orchestral terms. ... Another difficulty is that Francis, though there are things I love in his music, has passages that are strangely clumsy and that I long to rewrite, but of course I can't add or subtract anything and I should only spoil the whole thing \u2026 I have to think all the time of how he would have wanted it to sound.<ref name=lb>Berkeley, pp. 212\u2013213</ref>|}}\nThe musicologist [[Roger Covell]] wrote of Berkeley's orchestration, \"It is hard to imagine the job being done better \u2026 this sonata-concerto has Poulenc's characteristic and attractive mixture of flippancy and tenderness\".<ref>Covell, Roger. \"Classical\", ''The Sydney Morning Herald'', 12 May 1986, p. 56</ref> ''[[The Musical Times]]'' commented in 1978 that \"the orchestration does complete justice to the composer. [It] adds a worthwhile new dimension to the music: the long-drawn sad melodic lines played by the flute, especially in the first two movements, are complemented in a way not possible on the piano\".<ref>O'Loughlin, Niall. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/959603 Review], ''The Musical Times'', September 1978, p. 770 {{subscription}}</ref>\n\nThe orchestral arrangement has been recorded by Galway with the [[Royal Philharmonic Orchestra]] and [[Charles Dutoit]], and later by Emily Beynon with the [[BBC National Orchestra of Wales]] and [[Bramwell Tovey]], Jennifer Stinton with the [[Scottish Chamber Orchestra]] and [[Steuart Bedford]], and Bezaly with the Residentie Orkest Den Haag and [[Neeme J\u00e4rvi]].<ref>[https://www.worldcat.org/search?q=Poulenc+Lennox+Berkeley+Flute+Sonata&qt=results_page \"Poulenc Lennox Berkeley Flute Sonata\"], WorldCat. Retrieved 7 April 2020</ref>                    \n==Notes, references and sources==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=n}}\n===References===\n{{Reflist}}\n===Sources===\n\n* {{cite book | last= Berkeley | first= Lennox |editor= Peter Dickinson| title= Lennox Berkeley and Friends  Writings, Letters and Interviews| year= 2012| location= Woodbridge | publisher= Boydell | isbn= 978-1-84383-785-5}}\n* {{cite book | last= Mellers| first=Wilfrid | title=Francis Poulenc | year= 1995| location=Oxford and New York | publisher=Oxford University Press | isbn= }}\n* {{cite book | last=Nichols | first=Roger | title=Poulenc | year= 2020| location=New Haven | publisher=Yale University Press | isbn=978-0-300-22650-8 }}\n*{{cite journal  |last= Rifkin |first= Deborah | title = Making it Modern: Chromaticism and Phrase Structure in Twentieth-Century Tonal Music |journal = Theory and Practice  | date = 2006 |volume = 31 | pages = 133\u2013158 |url = https://www.jstor.org/stable/41054376}} {{subscription}} \n* {{cite book | last= Schmidt | first= Carl B | year= 2001| title= Entrancing Muse: A Documented Biography of Francis Poulenc | location= Hillsdale, US | publisher= Pendragon Press | isbn= 978-1-57647-026-8}}\n\n* {{cite book | last= Schmidt | first= Carl B| title= The Music of Francis Poulenc (1899-1963): a catalogue| year= 2002| location Oxford = | publisher= Clarendon Press | isbn= 978-0-19-816336-7}}\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.poulenc.fr poulenc.fr]\n\n{{Francis Poulenc}}\n{{Sonatas}}\n\n[[Category:Compositions by Francis Poulenc]]\n[[Category:Flute sonatas|Poulenc]]\n[[Category:1957 compositions]]\n[[Category:Funerary and memorial compositions]]\n", "text_old": "The '''''Sonate pour fl\u00fbte et piano''''' ('''Flute Sonata'''), [[FP (Poulenc)|FP]] 164, by [[Francis Poulenc]], for [[flute]] and [[piano]], was written in 1957. It is dedicated to the memory of [[Elizabeth Sprague Coolidge]], an American patron of chamber music.  Poulenc composed it for the flautist [[Jean-Pierre Rampal]], and he and Rampal gave the premi\u00e8re in June 1957 at the [[Strasbourg Music Festival]]. It is now one of Poulenc's best known works and is a prominent feature in 20th-century flute repertoire.\n\n==Background and first performance==\nPoulenc began to think of writing a flute sonata in 1952, but he was occupied with his Sonata for Two Pianos and then his opera, ''[[Dialogues of the Carmelites|Dialogues des Carm\u00e9lites]]''.<ref name=nimbus>Clements, Dominy (2015). Notes to Nimbus CD NI 5933</ref> In April 1956, when he was still working on the opera, he was approached by [[Harold Spivacke]] of the American [[Library of Congress]] with a request to write a piece for two pianos or alternatively a chamber piece for up to six instruments.<ref>Schmidt (2001), p. 408</ref> Poulenc was too busy to accept, but Spivacke persisted. Poulenc told him, \"Much more at home with wind instruments than strings, I admit I am tempted by this combination\",{{refn|Poulenc had always preferred winds \u2013 with their similarities to the human voice \u2013 to stringed instruments: \"nothing could be further from human breath than the stroke of a bow\". He thought little of his own sonatas for cello and for violin.<ref>Mellers, pp. 160\u2013161</ref>|group=n}}            and in August he agreed to go ahead.<ref name=ib>Battioni, Isabelle (2000). Notes to Naxos CD 8.553611</ref> The sonata was commissioned in memory of a musical benefactor, [[Elizabeth Sprague Coolidge]], to whom Poulenc dedicated the work.<ref name=nimbus/> \n\nPoulenc spent the winter of 1956\u201357 in [[Cannes]], where he composed the sonata between December and March.<ref name=mm>Malcolm MacDonald (2013). Notes to Opus Arte CD OACD9012D</ref> When he had completed the first two of the three movements, he wrote to his friend [[Pierre Bernac]]:\n{{blockindent|In working on this Flute Sonata I have the feeling of going back a long way, but with a more settled technique. It's a sonata of [[Claude Debussy|Debussyan]] dimensions. It's the French sense of balance [''la mesure fran\u00e7aise'']. Finding the form for your language is the most difficult thing. It's what [[Anton Webern|Webern]] has in the highest degree \u2026 and what [[Pierre Boulez|Boulez]] has not yet found.<ref>Nichols, p. 251</ref>|}}\n\nOn 18 June 1957, the public premiere was given by the flautist [[Jean-Pierre Rampal]], with the composer at the piano, at the [[Strasbourg Music Festival]].<ref name=hype>Mawer, Deborah (2001). Notes to Hyperion CD CDH55386</ref>{{refn|Rampal and Poulenc had given gave the work a private performance the previous day to an audience of one: the pianist [[Arthur Rubinstein]], who could not be present at the official premiere.<ref name=mm/>|group=n}}\n\n==Music==\nThe sonata is in three movements.The musicologist [[Malcolm MacDonald (music critic)|Malcolm MacDonald]] writes:\n{{block indent|The work is infused with Poulenc\u2019s trademark bittersweet grace, wit, irony and sentiment, which are manifested in different ways in each of its three movements. The first \u2026 makes clear the composer\u2019s elegiac intentions; the second is a haunting cantilena for the flute. Very fast and very tricky for the players, the skittish and vivacious \u2026 finale brings the work to a close in cheerful and sardonic style.<ref name=mm/>}}\n===''Allegretto malincolico''===\nThe movement starts in {{music|time|2|4}} with an opening four-bar phrase with a descending theme, beginning with a broken [[Triad (music)|triad]] of [[Thirty-second note |demisemiquavers]] around high E and declining to the G above [[C  (musical  note)#Middle  C |middle C]]. The piano's right hand part interweaves arpeggiated semiquavers over a [[pedal point|pedal]] in the left hand.<ref name=m156>Mellers, p. 156</ref> This is followed by an upward scale by both flute and piano leading to a contrasting theme, also descending.<ref>Rifkin,  pp. 141\u2013142</ref> The musicologist [[Malcolm MacDonald (music critic)|Malcolm MacDonald]] comments that the opening \"makes clear the composer\u2019s elegiac intentions\", and other analysts write of the \"poignancy\" of the principal theme, despite the seemingly vivacious tempo.<ref name=nimbus/><ref name=mm/><ref name=m163>Mellers, p. 163</ref> A counter-theme in F major gives the flute upwardly-leaping [[arpeggio]]s, before the opening theme returns in A minor. [[Wilfrid Mellers]] comments that the reappearance of the first theme in an unexpected key makes it clear that Poulenc is not following [[sonata form]] but is using \"a subtle ternary structure\".<ref name=m163/> After a slightly faster middle section there is a recapitulation of a kind, with, in Mellers's words \"enharmonic ambiguities that justify the 'malinconico' of the directive\", and:\n\n{{blockindent|Fragments of the first section's airborne melody intermingle with ecstatic spurtings of the middle theme. A coda to the coda is explicitly based on [[blue note|blue]] false relations between major and minor thirds.<ref>Mellers, p. 164</ref>|}}\n\nThe flute part is technically demanding in this movement, with frequent trills and demisemiquaver tonguing.<ref name=hype/>\n===''Cantilena: Assez lent''===\nThis movement is much slower and quieter. It begins with two quavers on the piano, which are echoed by the flute during the course of the next two bars. The haunting tune features minimal decoration, and is accompanied by flowing quavers on the piano. In the middle of the piece, the atmosphere suddenly changes to loud high notes on the flute, reaching a top B. However soon after it returns to the original slow tune. \n\n===''Presto giocoso''===\nThis movement is predominantly loud and fast, and Poulenc's \"trademark motif\" mentioned above reappears in the contrasting central section.\n\n==Later concert performances and recordings==\nPoulenc considered giving the American premiere together with Rampal during a planned US tour, but the tour did not take place and Rampal gave the American premiere in February 1958 with his regular accompanist [[Robert Veyron-Lacroix]].<ref>Schmidt (2002), p. 464</ref> Poulenc was pleased to accompany other flautists in the sonata. In January 1959 he accompanied [[Gareth Morris]] in the British premiere, in an all-Poulenc programme that included the world premiere of his ''\u00c9l\u00e9gie in memory of Dennis Brain'' for horn and piano.<ref>\"[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/1341c32439144c329b0ff1b9569f02d6?page=35 Third Programme]\", ''Radio Times'', 14 February 1959, p. 31</ref> Later in that year Poulenc played the piano part with [[Maxence Larrieu]] in [[Avignon]], Rampal in Paris and [[Christian Lard\u00e9]] in [[Menton]]. in 2015, the pianist and scholar [[David Owen Norris]] called the sonata \"probably the world's most played piece for flute and piano\".<ref name=bal>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sounds/play/p0381qw0 \"Building a Library\"], BBC Radio 3, 14 November 2015. Statement made at 1 minute from start. The survey is reported in the BBC's Music Magazine at [http://www.classical-music.com/article/best-recordings-poulencs-flute-sonata\" The best recordings of Poulenc's Flute Sonata\"], BBC. Retrieved 7 April 2020</ref>\n\n===Recordings===\nThe American premiere was recorded, as was the composer's Paris performance with Rampal.<ref>Car\u00e9, pp. 39\u201340</ref> There have been many subsequent recordings of the sonata. Among the earlier ones are those by [[Michel Debost]] with [[Jacques Fevrier]] and Rampal with Veyron-Lacroix. Later recordings include those by [[Julius Baker]] with Lisa Logan and [[Mathieu Dufour]] with [[\u00c9ric Le Sage]]. Among recordings singled out in a [[BBC Radio 3]] survey in 2015 are those by  [[William Bennett (flautist)|William Bennett]] with Clifford Benson; [[Sharon Bezaly]] with [[Ronald Brautigam]]; [[Patrick Gallois]] with [[Pascal Rog\u00e9]] ; [[Emmanuel Pahud]] with Le Sage]; Ileana Ruhemann with [[Kathron Sturrock]]; and [[Adam Walker (flautist)|Adam Walker]] with James Baillieu.<ref name=bal/>\n\n==Orchestral version==\nIn 1976 the flautist [[James Galway]] asked the English composer [[Lennox Berkeley|Sir Lennox Berkeley]], a good friend of Poulenc's for many years, to orchestrate the sonata.<ref name=lb/> While working on it, Berkeley wrote in his diary:\n{{blockindent|The task of orchestrating Poulenc's Flute Sonata ... proves as difficult as I had feared. ... The difficulty is the entirely pianistic nature of the accompaniment, extremely difficult to translate into orchestral terms. ... Another difficulty is that Francis, though there are things I love in his music, has passages that are strangely clumsy and that I long to rewrite, but of course I can't add or subtract anything and I should only spoil the whole thing \u2026 I have to think all the time of how he would have wanted it to sound.<ref name=lb>Berkeley, pp. 212\u2013213</ref>|}}\nThe musicologist [[Roger Covell]] wrote of Berkeley's orchestration, \"It is hard to imagine the job being done better \u2026 this sonata-concerto has Poulenc's characteristic and attractive mixture of flippancy and tenderness\".<ref>Covell, Roger. \"Classical\", ''The Sydney Morning Herald'', 12 May 1986, p. 56</ref> ''[[The Musical Times]]'' commented in 1978 that \"the orchestration does complete justice to the composer. [It] adds a worthwhile new dimension to the music: the long-drawn sad melodic lines played by the flute, especially in the first two movements, are complemented in a way not possible on the piano\".<ref>O'Loughlin, Niall. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/959603 Review], ''The Musical Times'', September 1978, p. 770 {{subscription}}</ref>\n\nThe orchestral arrangement has been recorded by Galway with the [[Royal Philharmonic Orchestra]] and [[Charles Dutoit]], and later by Emily Beynon with the [[BBC National Orchestra of Wales]] and [[Bramwell Tovey]], Jennifer Stinton with the [[Scottish Chamber Orchestra]] and [[Steuart Bedford]], and Bezaly with the Residentie Orkest Den Haag and [[Neeme J\u00e4rvi]].<ref>[https://www.worldcat.org/search?q=Poulenc+Lennox+Berkeley+Flute+Sonata&qt=results_page \"Poulenc Lennox Berkeley Flute Sonata\"], WorldCat. Retrieved 7 April 2020</ref>                    \n==Notes, references and sources==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=n}}\n===References===\n{{Reflist}}\n===Sources===\n\n* {{cite book | last= Berkeley | first= Lennox |editor= Peter Dickinson| title= Lennox Berkeley and Friends  Writings, Letters and Interviews| year= 2012| location= Woodbridge | publisher= Boydell | isbn= 978-1-84383-785-5}}\n* {{cite book | last= Mellers| first=Wilfrid | title=Francis Poulenc | year= 1995| location=Oxford and New York | publisher=Oxford University Press | isbn= }}\n* {{cite book | last=Nichols | first=Roger | title=Poulenc | year= 2020| location=New Haven | publisher=Yale University Press | isbn=978-0-300-22650-8 }}\n*{{cite journal  |last= Rifkin |first= Deborah | title = Making it Modern: Chromaticism and Phrase Structure in Twentieth-Century Tonal Music |journal = Theory and Practice  | date = 2006 |volume = 31 | pages = 133\u2013158 |url = https://www.jstor.org/stable/41054376}} {{subscription}} \n* {{cite book | last= Schmidt | first= Carl B | year= 2001| title= Entrancing Muse: A Documented Biography of Francis Poulenc | location= Hillsdale, US | publisher= Pendragon Press | isbn= 978-1-57647-026-8}}\n\n* {{cite book | last= Schmidt | first= Carl B| title= The Music of Francis Poulenc (1899-1963): a catalogue| year= 2002| location Oxford = | publisher= Clarendon Press | isbn= 978-0-19-816336-7}}\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.poulenc.fr poulenc.fr]\n\n{{Francis Poulenc}}\n{{Sonatas}}\n\n[[Category:Compositions by Francis Poulenc]]\n[[Category:Flute sonatas|Poulenc]]\n[[Category:1957 compositions]]\n[[Category:Funerary and memorial compositions]]\n", "name_user": "Tim riley", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRecordings:space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flute_Sonata_(Poulenc)"}
{"title_page": "Paulo Scott", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Paulo Scott\n| image              = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Paulo Scott\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1966|12|08}}\n| birth_place        = [[Porto Alegre, Brazil]]\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = Brazilian\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Author, playwright, screenwriter, translator\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n}}\n\n'''Paulo Scott''' (born 8 December 1966) is a Brazilian author, playwright, screenwriter and translator.\n\nHe studied law at [[Pontifical Catholic University of Rio Grande do Sul]] (PUCRS-RG).\n\nHe has received numerous awards including the ''Pr\u00eamio Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Biblioteca Nacional,'' and been shortlisted for renowned prizes like the ''[[Pr\u00eamio Jabuti]]'' and the ''[[S\u00e3o Paulo Prize for Literature|Pr\u00eamio S\u00e3o Paulo de Literatura]]''. His short story collection ''Still Orangutans'' was adapted into a movie and won the [[Milan Film Festival|Milano Film Festival]] in 2008.\n\nIn 2014, his novel ''Nowhere People'' was published in English (trans. [[Daniel Hahn]]) by [[And Other Stories]]. It was featured on ''[[World Literature Today]]''\u2019s list of \u2018[https://www.worldliteraturetoday.org/blog/translation-tuesday/75-notable-translations-2014 Notable Translations in 2014]\u2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldliteraturetoday.org/blog/translation-tuesday/75-notable-translations-2014|title=75 Notable Translations of 2014|date=2014-12-23|website=World Literature Today|language=en|access-date=2019-05-09}}</ref>\n\nHe currently lives in [[Rio de Janeiro]].\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scott, Paulo}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Brazilian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Brazilian screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Brazilian translators]]\n[[Category:People from Porto Alegre]]\n[[Category:20th-century Brazilian short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Brazilian novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Brazilian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Brazilian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:21st-century Brazilian short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Brazilian novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Brazilian male writers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Brazilian male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian male novelists]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Paulo Scott\n| image              = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Paulo Scott\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1966|12|08}}\n| birth_place        = [[Porto Alegre, Brazil]]\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = Brazilian\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Author, playwright, screenwriter, translator\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n}}\n\n'''Paulo Scott''' (born 8 December, 1966) is a Brazilian author, playwright, screenwriter and translator. \n\nHe studied law at [[Pontifical Catholic University of Rio Grande do Sul]] (PUCRS-RG).\n\nHe has received numerous awards including the ''Pr\u00eamio Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Biblioteca Nacional,'' and been shortlisted for renowned prizes like the ''[[Pr\u00eamio Jabuti]]'' and the ''[[S\u00e3o Paulo Prize for Literature|Pr\u00eamio S\u00e3o Paulo de Literatura]]''. His short story collection ''Still Orangutans'' was adapted into a movie and won the [[Milan Film Festival|Milano Film Festival]] in 2008. \n\nIn 2014, his novel ''Nowhere People'' was published in English (trans. [[Daniel Hahn]]) by [[And Other Stories]]. It was featured on ''[[World Literature Today]]''\u2019s list of \u2018[https://www.worldliteraturetoday.org/blog/translation-tuesday/75-notable-translations-2014 Notable Translations in 2014]\u2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldliteraturetoday.org/blog/translation-tuesday/75-notable-translations-2014|title=75 Notable Translations of 2014|date=2014-12-23|website=World Literature Today|language=en|access-date=2019-05-09}}</ref>\n\nHe currently lives in [[Rio de Janeiro]].\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scott, Paulo}}\n\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Brazilian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Brazilian screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Brazilian translators]]\n[[Category: People from Porto Alegre]]\n[[Category:20th-century Brazilian short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Brazilian novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Brazilian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Brazilian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:21st-century Brazilian short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Brazilian novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Brazilian male writers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Brazilian male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian male novelists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paulo_Scott"}
{"title_page": "Sling Aircraft Sling 2", "text_new": "{|{{Infobox aircraft begin\n |name = Sling 2\n |image = Sling2_OnGround_ZUSOL.jpg\n |caption = Sling 2\n}}\n{{Infobox aircraft type\n |type = [[Light Sport Aircraft]]\n |manufacturer= [[Sling Aircraft]]\n |designer = Mike Blyth\n |first flight= 18 November 2008 \n |introduced  = 2009\n |produced = \n |number built= 60 (2012)<ref name=\"KitplanesDec2012\"/>\n |unit cost = [[US$]]26,000 (kit only, 2012)<ref name=\"KitplanesDec2012\"/>\n | developed from= \n | variants with their own articles= [[Sling Aircraft Sling 4]]\n}}\n|}\n[[File:RA-Aus Sling 2 Registration 24-8489.JPG|thumb|A Sling 2]]\n[[File:RA-Aus Sling 2 Cockpit Registration 24-8489.JPG|thumb|Sling 2 instrument panel]]\nThe ''Sling Aircraft Sling 2'', formerly called '''The Airplane Factory Sling 2''', is a [[South Africa]]n two-seater [[light aircraft]] designed and produced by [[Sling Aircraft]] in Johannesburg, South Africa.<ref name=\"APilot_10\">''African Pilot'', Athol Franz, ''The Aircraft Factory Sling'', Dec 2010, Volume 9, Number 12, pp. 70\u201371.</ref> In 2009 the specially modified second prototype was flown around the world in a westerly circumnavigation which took 40 days.<ref name=\"P&P\">{{cite news |url=http://light-sport-hangar-flyin.blogspot.com/2010/01/around-world-in-40-lsa-days.html |publisher=Plane & Pilot Magazine |title=Around the World in 40 LSA Days |accessdate=12 June 2012}}</ref> This was the first time any aircraft of this class had achieved a circumnavigation.<ref name=\"SAFlyer_09\">''SA Flyer'', Guy Leitch, ''Sling around the world'', Oct 2009, No. 168, pp. 20\u201328.</ref> The design complies with the requirements of four different regulatory aircraft classes.<ref name=\"Dan Johnson\">{{cite news |url=http://www.bydanjohnson.com/showsplog.cfm?id=1621 |title=Out of Steam? No Way! Welcome to Sling |accessdate=12 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"S-LSA vs E-LSA\">{{cite news |url=http://www.aviatorshotline.com/content/lsa-registration-categorieswhat%E2%80%99s-difference |title=LSA Registration Categories...What's the Difference? |accessdate=18 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe design was originally known as the Sling, but was re-designated as the Sling 2 to distinguish it from the later four-seat [[Sling Aircraft Sling 4|Sling 4]].\n\nThe Sling 2 is supplied as a kit and as a ready-to-fly aircraft and can be operated as a [[light-sport aircraft]] or [[homebuilt aircraft]].\n\n==Design and development==\nDevelopment of the Sling 2 commenced in 2006. The Sling is a two-seat, low wing, all metal aircraft with [[tricycle landing gear]] made from composites. The aircraft is powered by a {{convert|100|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} [[Rotax 912ULS]], or a 912iS engine, or optionally a [[turbocharged]] {{convert|115|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} [[Rotax 914 UL]], driving a 3-bladed [[Warp Drive Inc]] propeller. The airplane features a sliding canopy, large fuel tanks, and standard equipment includes a \"glass cockpit\" style display.<ref name=\"KitplanesDec2012\">Bernard, Mary and Suzanne B. Bopp: ''The Airplane Factory: Sling 2 (and Sling 4)'', Kitplanes, Volume 29, Number 12, December 2012, page 22. Belvoir Publications. {{ISSN|0891-1851}}</ref><ref name=\"APilot_10\" /><ref name=\"EAA\">{{cite news |url=http://www.eaa.org/news/2012/2012-05-22_sling.asp |title=Sling Receives First S-LSA Certification |accessdate=12 June 2012 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120526012743/http://www.eaa.org/news/2012/2012-05-22_sling.asp |archivedate=26 May 2012 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"WDLA15\">Tacke, Willi; Marino Boric; et al: ''World Directory of Light Aviation 2015\u201316'', page 83. Flying Pages Europe SARL, 2015. {{ISSN|1368-485X}}</ref><ref name=\"Official\">{{cite web|url = https://www.slingaircraft.com/aircraft/sling-2/|title = Sling 2|access-date = 13 March 2020|author=[[Sling Aircraft]] |work = www.slingaircraft.com|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200313190044/https://www.slingaircraft.com/aircraft/sling-2/|archivedate = 13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMike Blyth began working on the design of the Sling 2 in 2006; the first prototype first flew on November 18, 2008. A full testing programme followed, with the help of a South African military aerodynamicist, which was completed in 2009. Blyth and partner James Pitman then flew the second prototype around the world to accomplish a challenging circumnavigation.<ref name=\"SAFlyer_09\" /><ref name=\"TAF USA Website\">{{cite news |url=http://www.airplanefactory.com/aircraft/design-construction/ |title=Sling Design & Construction |accessdate=14 June 2012 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625054811/http://www.airplanefactory.com/aircraft/design-construction/ |archivedate=25 June 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\nSixty Sling 2s had been completed and flown by the end of 2012.<ref name=\"KitplanesDec2012\" /><ref name=\"The Airplane Factory Aero-News Announcement\">{{cite news |url=http://www.aero-news.net/index.cfm?do=main.textpost&id=1da105fa-ed8b-42a5-b66f-b9c503a1d648 |title=Sling S-LSA Aero-News Announcement |accessdate=14 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Operational history==\n\nThe second prototype Sling 2 was flown on a westerly global circumnavigation in 2009. Blyth and Pitman departed from South Africa flying up through Western Africa, across the Atlantic to Brazil and Guyana, up through the US Virgin Islands and the East Coast of the United States to [[Oshkosh, Wisconsin]] for [[EAA AirVenture Oshkosh]] 2009. After the [[air show]] they flew across the United States to Los Angeles, then on to Hawaii, the Marshall Islands, Micronesia, Indonesia, Malaysia, Sri Lanka, Seychelles, and finally back to South Africa. They completed the whole journey in 40 days.<ref name=\"P&P\" /> The aircraft used for the circumnavigation was a standard production Sling, but with larger {{convert|118.8|u.s.gal}} fuel tanks, strengthened landing gear, seats that lie flat for sleeping and removable control sticks.<ref name=\"Spirit\">{{cite news |url=http://www.airventure.org/news/2009/090729_sling.html |title=Spirit of Adventure |accessdate=12 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Sling mods\">{{cite news |url=http://airplanefactory.co.za/world/aircraft.asp |title=Around the World Sling Modifications |accessdate=15 June 2012 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090725231957/http://airplanefactory.co.za/world/aircraft.asp |archivedate=25 July 2009 |df= }}</ref> After being modified, the aircraft had an endurance at standard cruise of approximately 24 hours. The aircraft cruised at 89 knots [[Indicated airspeed]] (IAS) (98 knots [[True airspeed]] (TAS)) with almost full fuel. When more nearly empty, it would cruise at 96 knots IAS (105 knots TAS). With full fuel, fully loaded with crew the Sling weighed approximately 1,984 Lbs (900&nbsp;kg), or about 600 pounds overweight. At sea level the aircraft would climb slowly, at a rate of 350 feet per minute.<ref name=\"KitplanesDec2012\" /><ref name=\"SAFlyer_09\" /><ref name=\"Sling mods\" />\n\n==Specifications (2012 model Sling 2)==\n[[File:TAF Sling2 pairZUTAEandZUNRC.jpg|thumb|A pair of Sling 2s in formation]]\n{{Aircraft specs\n|ref=The Airplane Factory<ref name=\"TAF Sling Specs\">{{cite news |url=http://www.airplanefactory.com/aircraft/specifications/ |title=Sling Specifications |accessdate=18 June 2012 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625054301/http://www.airplanefactory.com/aircraft/specifications/ |archivedate=25 June 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n|prime units?=kts<!-- imp or kts first for US aircraft, and UK aircraft pre-metrification, \nmet(ric) first for all others. You MUST choose a format, or no specifications will show -->\n<!--\n        General characteristics\n-->\n|genhide=\n\n|crew=one \n|capacity=one passenger\n|length m=\n|length ft=22.89\n|length in=\n|length note=\n|span m=\n|span ft=30.09\n|span in=\n|span note=\n|height ft=8.202\n|height in=\n|height note=\n|wing area sqm=\n|wing area sqft=127.5\n|wing area note=\n|aspect ratio=7.04:1\n|airfoil=\n|empty weight kg=370\n|empty weight lb=\n|empty weight note=\n|gross weight kg=700\n|gross weight lb=\n|gross weight note=<ref name=\"Official\" />\n|fuel capacity=Two tanks with {{convert|19.3|u.s.gal}} usable\n|more general=\n<!--\n        Powerplant\n-->\n|eng1 number=1\n|eng1 name=[[Rotax 912ULS]]\n|eng1 type=\n|eng1 kw=\n|eng1 hp=100\n\n|prop blade number=3\n|prop name=[[Warp Drive Inc]] composite \n|prop dia m=\n|prop dia ft=\n|prop dia in=70\n|prop dia note=\n\n<!--\n        Performance\n-->\n|perfhide=\n\n|max speed kmh=\n|max speed mph=\n|max speed kts=\n|max speed note=\n|cruise speed kmh=\n|cruise speed mph=\n|cruise speed kts=120\n|cruise speed note=[[true airspeed]]<ref name=\"Official\" />\n|stall speed kmh=\n|stall speed mph=\n|stall speed kts=40\n|stall speed note=full flaps, [[indicated airspeed]]\n|never exceed speed kmh=\n|never exceed speed mph=\n|never exceed speed kts=135\n|never exceed speed note=[[indicated airspeed]]\n|range km=\n|range miles=\n|range nmi=\n|range note=\n|endurance=\n|ceiling m=\n|ceiling ft=13000\n|ceiling note=\n|g limits=+4/-2 g\n|roll rate=\n|glide ratio=\n|climb rate ms=\n|climb rate ftmin=\n|climb rate note=\n|wing loading kg/m2=\n|wing loading lb/sqft=12.10\n|wing loading note=\n|fuel consumption kg/km=\n|fuel consumption lb/mi=\n|power/mass=\n|more performance=\n|avionics=\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{aircontent\n|see also=\n|related=\n|similar aircraft=\n*[[Rans S-19 Venterra]]\n*[[Sonaca 200]]\n*[[Van's Aircraft RV-12]]\n|lists=\n|similar engines=\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|The Airplane Factory Sling 2}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.slingaircraft.com/aircraft/sling-2/}}\n* [http://aeropunk.com/blog/general/around-the-world-in-an-e-lsa/ EAA Oshkosh Video about Sling LSA Around the World]\n{{Sling Aircraft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Airplane Factory Sling}}\n[[Category:2000s South African aircraft]]\n[[Category:Light-sport aircraft]]\n[[Category:Aircraft first flown in 2008]]\n[[Category:Low-wing aircraft]]\n[[Category:Single-engined tractor aircraft]]\n[[Category:Homebuilt aircraft]]\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox aircraft begin\n |name = Sling 2\n |image = Sling2_OnGround_ZUSOL.jpg\n |caption = Sling 2\n}}\n{{Infobox aircraft type\n |type = [[Light Sport Aircraft]]\n |manufacturer= [[Sling Aircraft]]\n |designer = Mike Blyth\n |first flight= 18 November 2008 \n |introduced  = 2009\n |produced = \n |number built= 60 (2012)<ref name=\"KitplanesDec2012\"/>\n |unit cost = [[US$]]26,000 (kit only, 2012)<ref name=\"KitplanesDec2012\"/>\n | developed from= \n | variants with their own articles= [[Sling Aircraft Sling 4]]\n}}\n|}\n[[File:RA-Aus Sling 2 Registration 24-8489.JPG|thumb|A Sling 2]]\n[[File:RA-Aus Sling 2 Cockpit Registration 24-8489.JPG|thumb|Sling 2 instrument panel]]\nThe ''Sling Aircraft Sling 2'', formerly called '''The Airplane Factory Sling 2''', is a [[South Africa]]n two-seater [[light aircraft]] designed and produced by [[Sling Aircraft]] in Johannesburg, South Africa.<ref name=\"APilot_10\">''African Pilot'', Athol Franz, ''The Aircraft Factory Sling'', Dec 2010, Volume 9, Number 12, pp. 70\u201371.</ref> In 2009 the specially modified second prototype was flown around the world in a westerly circumnavigation which took 40 days.<ref name=\"P&P\">{{cite news |url=http://light-sport-hangar-flyin.blogspot.com/2010/01/around-world-in-40-lsa-days.html |publisher=Plane & Pilot Magazine |title=Around the World in 40 LSA Days |accessdate=12 June 2012}}</ref> This was the first time any aircraft of this class had achieved a circumnavigation.<ref name=\"SAFlyer_09\">''SA Flyer'', Guy Leitch, ''Sling around the world'', Oct 2009, No. 168, pp. 20\u201328.</ref> The design complies with the requirements of four different regulatory aircraft classes.<ref name=\"Dan Johnson\">{{cite news |url=http://www.bydanjohnson.com/showsplog.cfm?id=1621 |title=Out of Steam? No Way! Welcome to Sling |accessdate=12 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"S-LSA vs E-LSA\">{{cite news |url=http://www.aviatorshotline.com/content/lsa-registration-categorieswhat%E2%80%99s-difference |title=LSA Registration Categories...What's the Difference? |accessdate=18 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe design was originally known as the Sling, but was re-designated as the Sling 2 to distinguish it from the later four-seat [[Sling Aircraft Sling 4|Sling 4]].\n\nThe Sling 2 is supplied as a kit and as a ready-to-fly aircraft and can be operated as a [[light-sport aircraft]] or [[homebuilt aircraft]].\n\n==Design and development==\nDevelopment of the Sling 2 commenced in 2006. The Sling is a two-seat, low wing, all metal aircraft with [[tricycle landing gear]] made from composites. The aircraft is powered by an {{convert|80|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} [[Rotax 912UL]],{{convert|100|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}}, a [[Rotax 912ULS]], or a 912iS engine, or optionally a [[turbocharged]] {{convert|115|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} [[Rotax 914 UL]], driving a 3-bladed [[Warp Drive Inc]] propeller. The factory later discontinued the {{convert|80|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} [[Rotax 912UL]] model. The airplane features a sliding canopy, large fuel tanks, and standard equipment includes a \"glass cockpit\" style display.<ref name=\"KitplanesDec2012\">Bernard, Mary and Suzanne B. Bopp: ''The Airplane Factory: Sling 2 (and Sling 4)'', Kitplanes, Volume 29, Number 12, December 2012, page 22. Belvoir Publications. {{ISSN|0891-1851}}</ref><ref name=\"APilot_10\" /><ref name=\"EAA\">{{cite news |url=http://www.eaa.org/news/2012/2012-05-22_sling.asp |title=Sling Receives First S-LSA Certification |accessdate=12 June 2012 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120526012743/http://www.eaa.org/news/2012/2012-05-22_sling.asp |archivedate=26 May 2012 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"WDLA15\">Tacke, Willi; Marino Boric; et al: ''World Directory of Light Aviation 2015\u201316'', page 83. Flying Pages Europe SARL, 2015. {{ISSN|1368-485X}}</ref><ref name=\"Official\">{{cite web|url = https://www.slingaircraft.com/aircraft/sling-2/|title = Sling 2|access-date = 13 March 2020|author=[[Sling Aircraft]] |work = www.slingaircraft.com|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20200313190044/https://www.slingaircraft.com/aircraft/sling-2/|archivedate = 13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMike Blyth began working on the design of the Sling 2 in 2006; the first prototype first flew on November 18, 2008. A full testing programme followed, with the help of a South African military aerodynamicist, which was completed in 2009. Blyth and partner James Pitman then flew the second prototype around the world to accomplish a challenging circumnavigation.<ref name=\"SAFlyer_09\" /><ref name=\"TAF USA Website\">{{cite news |url=http://www.airplanefactory.com/aircraft/design-construction/ |title=Sling Design & Construction |accessdate=14 June 2012 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625054811/http://www.airplanefactory.com/aircraft/design-construction/ |archivedate=25 June 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\nSixty Sling 2s had been completed and flown by the end of 2012.<ref name=\"KitplanesDec2012\" /><ref name=\"The Airplane Factory Aero-News Announcement\">{{cite news |url=http://www.aero-news.net/index.cfm?do=main.textpost&id=1da105fa-ed8b-42a5-b66f-b9c503a1d648 |title=Sling S-LSA Aero-News Announcement |accessdate=14 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Operational history==\n\nThe second prototype Sling 2 was flown on a westerly global circumnavigation in 2009. Blyth and Pitman departed from South Africa flying up through Western Africa, across the Atlantic to Brazil and Guyana, up through the US Virgin Islands and the East Coast of the United States to [[Oshkosh, Wisconsin]] for [[EAA AirVenture Oshkosh]] 2009. After the [[air show]] they flew across the United States to Los Angeles, then on to Hawaii, the Marshall Islands, Micronesia, Indonesia, Malaysia, Sri Lanka, Seychelles, and finally back to South Africa. They completed the whole journey in 40 days.<ref name=\"P&P\" /> The aircraft used for the circumnavigation was a standard production Sling, but with larger {{convert|118.8|u.s.gal}} fuel tanks, strengthened landing gear, seats that lie flat for sleeping and removable control sticks.<ref name=\"Spirit\">{{cite news |url=http://www.airventure.org/news/2009/090729_sling.html |title=Spirit of Adventure |accessdate=12 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Sling mods\">{{cite news |url=http://airplanefactory.co.za/world/aircraft.asp |title=Around the World Sling Modifications |accessdate=15 June 2012 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090725231957/http://airplanefactory.co.za/world/aircraft.asp |archivedate=25 July 2009 |df= }}</ref> After being modified, the aircraft had an endurance at standard cruise of approximately 24 hours. The aircraft cruised at 89 knots [[Indicated airspeed]] (IAS) (98 knots [[True airspeed]] (TAS)) with almost full fuel. When more nearly empty, it would cruise at 96 knots IAS (105 knots TAS). With full fuel, fully loaded with crew the Sling weighed approximately 1,984 Lbs (900&nbsp;kg), or about 600 pounds overweight. At sea level the aircraft would climb slowly, at a rate of 350 feet per minute.<ref name=\"KitplanesDec2012\" /><ref name=\"SAFlyer_09\" /><ref name=\"Sling mods\" />\n\n==Specifications (2012 model Sling 2)==\n[[File:TAF Sling2 pairZUTAEandZUNRC.jpg|thumb|A pair of Sling 2s in formation]]\n{{Aircraft specs\n|ref=The Airplane Factory<ref name=\"TAF Sling Specs\">{{cite news |url=http://www.airplanefactory.com/aircraft/specifications/ |title=Sling Specifications |accessdate=18 June 2012 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625054301/http://www.airplanefactory.com/aircraft/specifications/ |archivedate=25 June 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n|prime units?=kts<!-- imp or kts first for US aircraft, and UK aircraft pre-metrification, \nmet(ric) first for all others. You MUST choose a format, or no specifications will show -->\n<!--\n        General characteristics\n-->\n|genhide=\n\n|crew=one \n|capacity=one passenger\n|length m=\n|length ft=22.89\n|length in=\n|length note=\n|span m=\n|span ft=30.09\n|span in=\n|span note=\n|height ft=8.202\n|height in=\n|height note=\n|wing area sqm=\n|wing area sqft=127.5\n|wing area note=\n|aspect ratio=7.04:1\n|airfoil=\n|empty weight kg=\n|empty weight lb=796\n|empty weight note=\n|gross weight kg=\n|gross weight lb=1320\n|gross weight note=\n|fuel capacity=Two tanks with {{convert|19.3|u.s.gal}} usable\n|more general=\n<!--\n        Powerplant\n-->\n|eng1 number=1\n|eng1 name=[[Rotax 912ULS]]\n|eng1 type=\n|eng1 kw=\n|eng1 hp=100\n\n|prop blade number=3\n|prop name=[[Warp Drive Inc]] composite \n|prop dia m=\n|prop dia ft=\n|prop dia in=70\n|prop dia note=\n\n<!--\n        Performance\n-->\n|perfhide=\n\n|max speed kmh=\n|max speed mph=\n|max speed kts=116\n|max speed note=[[indicated airspeed]]\n|cruise speed kmh=\n|cruise speed mph=\n|cruise speed kts=\n|cruise speed note=\n|stall speed kmh=\n|stall speed mph=\n|stall speed kts=45\n|stall speed note=\n|never exceed speed kmh=\n|never exceed speed mph=\n|never exceed speed kts=135\n|never exceed speed note=\n|range km=\n|range miles=\n|range nmi=\n|range note=\n|endurance=\n|ceiling m=\n|ceiling ft=12000\n|ceiling note=\n|g limits=+4/-2 g\n|roll rate=\n|glide ratio=\n|climb rate ms=\n|climb rate ftmin=\n|climb rate note=\n|wing loading kg/m2=\n|wing loading lb/sqft=12.10\n|wing loading note=\n|fuel consumption kg/km=\n|fuel consumption lb/mi=\n|power/mass=\n|more performance=\n|avionics=\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{aircontent\n|see also=\n|related=\n|similar aircraft=\n*[[Rans S-19 Venterra]]\n*[[Sonaca 200]]\n*[[Van's Aircraft RV-12]]\n|lists=\n|similar engines=\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|The Airplane Factory Sling 2}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.slingaircraft.com/aircraft/sling-2/}}\n* [http://aeropunk.com/blog/general/around-the-world-in-an-e-lsa/ EAA Oshkosh Video about Sling LSA Around the World]\n{{Sling Aircraft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Airplane Factory Sling}}\n[[Category:2000s South African aircraft]]\n[[Category:Light-sport aircraft]]\n[[Category:Aircraft first flown in 2008]]\n[[Category:Low-wing aircraft]]\n[[Category:Single-engined tractor aircraft]]\n[[Category:Homebuilt aircraft]]\n", "name_user": "Raladic", "label": "safe", "comment": "Small performance number fixes based on official manufacturer website data", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sling_Aircraft_Sling_2"}
{"title_page": "Exodus (American band)", "text_new": "{{redirect|Exodus (band)|the progressive rock band|Exodus (Polish band)}}\n{{short description|American thrash metal band}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Exodus\n| image = Exodus 2016231161029 2016-08-18 Summer Breeze - Sven - 1D X II - 0567 - AK8I5470 mod.jpg\n| caption = Exodus performing at the [[Summer Breeze Open Air]] festival in 2016\n| image_size = \n| landscape = yes\n| background = group_or_band\n| alias = \n| origin = [[Richmond, California]], U.S.\n| genre = [[Thrash metal]]\n| years_active = {{flatlist|\n* 1979\u20131994\n* 1997\u20131998\n* 2001\u2013present}}\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n* [[Century Media Records|Century Media]]\n* [[Combat Records|Combat]]\n* [[Nuclear Blast]]}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[Heathen (band)|Heathen]]\n* [[Hatriot (band)|Hatriot]]\n* [[Blind Illusion]]\n* [[Metallica]]\n* [[Possessed (band)|Possessed]]\n* [[Testament (band)|Testament]]\n* [[Slayer]]\n* [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]]\n* [[Megadeth]]\n* [[White Zombie (band)|White Zombie]]\n* [[Generation Kill (band)|Generation Kill]]}}\n\nPower Chord\n| website = [http://www.exodusattack.com/ www.exodusattack.com]\n| current_members = <!--Do not change, members are listed in order of joining the band as per Wikipedia guidelines.-->[[Gary Holt (musician)|Gary Holt]]<br>Jack Gibson<br>[[Lee Altus]]<br>[[Tom Hunting]]<br>[[Steve Souza|Steve \"Zetro\" Souza]]\n| past_members = [[List of Exodus members]]\n}}\n\n'''Exodus''' is an American [[thrash metal]] band formed in 1979 in [[Richmond, California]].<ref name=\"Enter Night\">{{cite book |last = Wall |first = Mick |title = Enter Night: A Biography of Metallica (page 119) |publisher = [[St. Martin's Press]] |date = May 10, 2011 |isbn = 0-312-64989-4}}</ref> They have gone through numerous lineup changes, two extended hiatuses, and the deaths of two former band members. Their current lineup consists of guitarists [[Gary Holt (musician)|Gary Holt]] and [[Lee Altus]], bassist Jack Gibson, drummer [[Tom Hunting]], and lead vocalist [[Steve Souza|Steve \"Zetro\" Souza]]. Hunting is one of the original members, and departed from Exodus twice, in 1989 and 2004, but rejoined in 2007. Holt joined the band about two years after its formation, and is the only member of Exodus to appear on all their releases.\n\nSince its formation, Exodus has released ten studio albums, two live albums, one compilation album, and a [[Let There Be Blood|re-recording]] of their [[Bonded by Blood|first album]]. Along with [[Metallica]] (whose longtime lead guitarist [[Kirk Hammett]] was an original member of Exodus), they are often credited as pioneers of the [[Bay Area thrash metal]] scene,<ref>{{cite web|title=Exodus To Release 'Blood In, Blood Out' Album In October|url=http://www2.gibson.com/News-Lifestyle/Shared/2011/June/Gibson-Interview-Kirk-Hammett-of-Metallica.aspx|work=[[Gibson Guitar Corporation|gibson.com]]|date=June 5, 2011|accessdate=October 12, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617193212/http://www.gibson.com/News-Lifestyle/Shared/2011/June/Gibson-Interview-Kirk-Hammett-of-Metallica.aspx|archive-date=June 17, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Legendary metal band Exodus, formed in Richmond, set to release 10th studio album|url=http://richmondstandard.com/2014/09/legendary-metal-band-exodus-formed-richmond-set-release-10th-studio-album/|work=richmondstandard.com|date=September 24, 2014|accessdate=October 12, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141019021512/http://richmondstandard.com/2014/09/legendary-metal-band-exodus-formed-richmond-set-release-10th-studio-album/|archive-date=October 19, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and have sold over five million albums worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegauntlet.com/article/29011/Exodus-Announces-Hometown-Gig |title=Exodus Announces Hometown Gig \u2013 The Gauntlet Heavy Metal News |website=Thegauntlet.com |date=October 3, 2013 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> Exodus is also considered to be as one the \"big eight\" of thrash metal, along with Metallica, [[Megadeth]], [[Slayer]], [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]], [[Testament (band)|Testament]], [[Overkill (band)|Overkill]] and [[Death Angel]].<ref name=\"da allmusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/death-angel-mn0000230845/biography|title=Death Angel Biography & History|work=[[AllMusic|allmusic.com]]|accessdate=October 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.herald-dispatch.com/features_entertainment/the-v-club-to-host-san-fran-thrash-metal-unit/article_75cf0136-81e9-5735-ba08-f275df1aed4d.html|title=The V Club to host San Fran thrash metal unit Death Angel|publisher=herald-dispatch.com|accessdate=October 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/mycity/news/legendary-metal-band-testament-to-be-part-of-silence-festival-2019|title=My City - Legendary metal band, Testament to be part of Silence Festival 2019|publisher=[[Rep\u00fablica (newspaper)|myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com]]|accessdate=October 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://metaljacketmagazine.com/metaldays-2020-first-bands-confirmed/|title=MetalDays 2020: First bands confirmed!|publisher=metaljacketmagazine.com|accessdate=October 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloodbath.ro/rockstadt-extreme-fest-2019-la-final-28-000-de-participanti-in-cele-4-zile-de-festival-si-50-de-trupe-au-concertat-pe-doua-scene-principale/|title=Rockstadt Extreme Fest 2019 la final: 28.000 de participan\u021bi \u00een cele 4 zile de festival \u0219i 50 de trupe au concertat pe dou\u0103 scene principale!|publisher=bloodbath.ro|accessdate=October 15, 2019}}</ref> The band had particular success in the mid-to-late 1980s with their first three studio albums: ''[[Bonded by Blood]]'' (1985), ''[[Pleasures of the Flesh]]'' (1987) and ''[[Fabulous Disaster]]'' (1989). The critical praise given to ''Fabulous Disaster'' garnered attention from major labels, including [[Capitol Records]], with whom Exodus signed in 1989. The band released two more studio albums (''[[Impact Is Imminent]]'' in 1990 and ''[[Force of Habit]]'' in 1992) before disbanding in 1994. After temporarily reuniting in 1997\u20131998, Exodus reformed once again in 2001, and since then, they have released five more studio albums, the most recent being ''[[Blood In, Blood Out (Exodus album)|Blood In, Blood Out]]'' (2014). The band is currently writing a follow-up album, tentatively due for release in 2020.<ref name=\"new album blabbermouth\">{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exoduss-next-album-will-be-very-violent-and-very-heavy/|title=EXODUS's Next Album Will Be 'Very Violent And Very Heavy'|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|date=August 6, 2018|accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Formation and early years (1979\u20131983)===\n[[File:Gary Holt Slayer Kiev 03.JPG|thumb|right|Guitarist [[Gary Holt (musician)|Gary Holt]] has been a member of Exodus since 1981, and is the only member to have performed on all of the band's albums.]]\n\nThe initial lineup of Exodus was formed in the late 1970s by guitarists [[Kirk Hammett]] and Tim Agnello, drummer/vocalist [[Tom Hunting]], and vocalist Keith Stewart, while they attended high school together. The band added bass guitarist Carlton Melson in 1980, and the quintet began making a name for themselves playing backyard parties and various school functions. They played mostly cover songs in the vein of 1970s hard rock and [[New wave of British heavy metal]] (NWOBHM) acts but also developed some of their own original songs. Stewart soon left the band and Hunting became the band's sole vocalist for some time. Carlton Melson was replaced in 1981 by bass guitarist Geoff Andrews.<ref>{{cite web|title=Carlton Melson interview|url=http://pestwebzine.com/index/carlton_melson/0-1457}}</ref> Tim Agnello would also leave the group, moving to New York City and staying involved in the music industry as a guitar player, manager, and writer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tim Agnello interview|url=https://www.cmalliance.org/alife/you-can-call-me-al/}}</ref> This left Exodus to perform as a power trio until a replacement was found in Hammett's friend and Exodus roadie [[Gary Holt (musician)|Gary Holt]].<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gvMDgl0z_ZA|title = Exodus / Slayer's Gary Holt \u2013 Wikipedia: Fact or Fiction?|date = April 8, 2015|accessdate = November 18, 2015|website = YouTube|publisher = LoudWire|last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nAlso in 1981, Hammett met El Cerrito resident [[Paul Baloff]] at a North Berkeley house party, a friendship that was started \u2013 according to Hammett \u2013 by their shared admiration for punk rock and 1970s heavy metal music. Baloff became the band's lead vocalist and the quintet recorded a 3-track demo tape in 1982 consisting of the songs \"Whipping Queen\", \"Death and Domination\" and \"Warlord\", a release which would be Hammett's only recording with Exodus. The band's music began to incorporate elements of [[hardcore punk]] into their NWOBHM roots, and Exodus was considered a pioneer of the [[Bay Area thrash metal]] scene. In November 1982, Exodus opened a show at San Francisco's [[Old Waldorf]] venue for [[Metallica]],<ref>[http://www.encycmet.com/live/26.shtml ENCYCLOPEDIA METALLICA \u2013 Concert Info: San Francisco, Old Waldorf California Nov 29, 1982] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090604222532/http://encycmet.com/live/26.shtml |date=June 4, 2009}}</ref> a then-relatively unknown (and unsigned) band from Los Angeles. As the band began playing more shows in Bay Area clubs, they gained a large, fervent fan base known for their violent concert behavior.\n\nIn early 1983, Hammett left Exodus to join [[Metallica]] on the recommendation of manager / producer [[Mark Whitaker (record producer)|Mark Whitaker]], leaving Gary Holt to effectively take creative control of the band. Hammett was replaced short term by Mike Maung, followed by [[Evan McCaskey]], before the band finally found a permanent replacement in guitarist [[Rick Hunolt]]. Geoff Andrews also left to start an early incarnation of pioneering [[death metal]] band [[Possessed (band)|Possessed]], and was replaced by bass guitarist Rob McKillop.\n\nIn the spring of 1984, Exodus entered Turk Street Studios with producer [[Doug Piercy]] to record demos of songs that would later appear on their debut album. The band was signed to New York-based Torrid Records and Exodus prepared to enter [[Prairie Sun Recording Studios]] that summer.\n\n===''Bonded By Blood'' and rise in popularity (1984\u20131991)===\n[[File:Exodus Rockharz 2018 30.jpg|thumb|left|Vocalist [[Steve Souza|Steve \"Zetro\" Souza]], who replaced [[Paul Baloff]], was a member of Exodus from 1986 to their first breakup in 1994, and again from 2002 to 2004. He rejoined the band once again in 2014.]]\nThe band recorded their first album, ''[[Bonded by Blood]]'', in the summer of 1984 with the band's manager [[Mark Whitaker (music producer)|Mark Whitaker]] producing. 1984 concert photos from Exodus shows at [[Aquatic Park (Berkeley)|Aquatic Park]]'s Eastern Front Metal Festival (with [[Slayer]] and [[Suicidal Tendencies]]) and [[Bay Area thrash metal#Ruthie's Inn, Berkeley|Ruthie's Inn]] (with [[Megadeth]] and Slayer) were included on the album sleeve inserts. Originally titled ''A Lesson in Violence'', the album was not released until April 1985 amidst creative and business setbacks. Whilst ''Bonded By Blood'' is considered a highly influential [[thrash metal]] album today, critics have regarded the delay in its release as having hindered the impact the album could have had. As Allmusic reviewer Eduardo Rivadavia would later write in his review for the album: \"Had it been released immediately after it was recorded in 1984, Exodus' ''Bonded by Blood'' might be regarded today alongside [[Metallica]]'s ''[[Kill 'Em All]]'' as one of the landmark albums responsible for launching the thrash metal wave.\"<ref name=allmusic>{{cite web|author=Eduardo Rivadavia |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/bonded-by-blood-mw0000192933 |title=Bonded by Blood \u2013 Exodus &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |date= |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> Exodus promoted the album by going on tour with [[Venom (band)|Venom]] and [[Slayer]]. Four songs from their performance of April 5, 1985 at Studio 54 in New York City were filmed and released on home video as ''Combat Tour Live: The Ultimate Revenge''. The band subsequently toured or played selected shows with bands like [[Exciter (band)|Exciter]], [[Megadeth]], [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]], [[King Diamond (band)|King Diamond]], [[Possessed (band)|Possessed]], [[Dirty Rotten Imbeciles|D.R.I.]], [[Nuclear Assault]] and [[Hirax]].\n\nShortly after touring for ''Bonded by Blood'' was complete, Paul Baloff was fired from the band allegedly due to his behavior related to alcohol and substance abuse, and was replaced by [[Steve Souza|Steve \"Zetro\" Souza]], who had previously been the lead vocalist for Legacy, an early incarnation of fellow Bay Area thrashers [[Testament (band)|Testament]]. Baloff went on to form the band Piranha in 1987.\n\nExodus' line-up remained stable for the recording of their next two albums, and the underground success attained with ''Bonded by Blood'' would lead to the group's signing to [[Sony Music|Sony]]/[[Combat Records]], who released the band's second effort ''[[Pleasures of the Flesh]]'' in 1987. The album was engineered by then-unknown [[Sylvia Massy]], who would go on to produce two releases by progressive metal band [[Tool (band)|Tool]]. In support of ''Pleasures of the Flesh'', Exodus toured with the likes of [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]], [[Celtic Frost]], [[M.O.D.]], [[L\u0227\u0227z Rockit]] and [[Testament (band)|Testament]].\n\n''[[Fabulous Disaster]]'', the group's third full-length album, was released in 1989. A [[music video]] for the song \"[[The Toxic Waltz (song)|The Toxic Waltz]]\" would receive consistent rotation on [[MTV]]'s ''[[Headbangers Ball]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.revolvermag.com/magazine/article/the-history-of-american-thrash |title=The History of American Thrash |publisher=[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver.com]] |accessdate=September 19, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125083043/http://www.revolvermag.com/magazine/article/the-history-of-american-thrash |archivedate=November 25, 2010}}</ref> While promoting ''Fabulous Disaster'', Exodus embarked on the [[Headbangers Ball Tour|Headbangers Ball]] tour with [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]] and [[Helloween]], which brought the band to a wider audience.\n\nAfter the success of ''Fabulous Disaster'', Exodus signed to [[Capitol Records]] in 1989, who released the band's fourth album ''[[Impact is Imminent]]'' the following year. Prior to recording the album, Tom Hunting left the band for personal reasons; he was replaced by [[John Tempesta]] on drums. In 1991, the band released their first live album, ''[[Good Friendly Violent Fun]]'', which was recorded during their 1989 tour.\n\n===''Force of Habit'', hiatus, and temporary reunion (1991\u20132000)===\n[[File:Exodus Rockharz 2018 33.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Jack Gibson joined Exodus in 1997 as bass guitarist and has been with the group ever since.]]\n\nAfter the release of ''Good Friendly Violent Fun'', the band toured sporadically for a year. Bass guitarist McKillop was replaced by Michael Butler before the group recorded and released their next studio album titled ''[[Force of Habit]]'' in 1992. This album was something of a departure from the band's signature sound, containing several slower, \"heavier\" songs with less emphasis on the thrash aspect of their older material. The 11-minute song \"Architect of Pain\" is a good example of the change of direction, having a much slower, grinding feel than the usual high tempo thrash they had become known for. After touring for ''Force of Habit'' was completed, behind-the-scenes issues as well as a changing musical environment prompted the band to split up.\n\nHolt and Hunting formed the groove / thrash metal outfit Wardance in the mid 1990s playing several shows around the Bay Area and recording a 4-song demo, but the group never gained momentum and eventually disbanded.\n\nHolt and Hunting reunited with Paul Baloff and Rick Hunolt for a short Exodus tour in 1997. The lineup was completed with Wardance bassist Jack Gibson. They released a live album titled ''[[Another Lesson in Violence]]'' recorded at the [[Trocadero Transfer]] in front of a home town audience. However, the group disbanded again the following year, in part due to a falling out with record label Century Media over the way promotion for the live album was handled, and over an aborted attempt at a live concert video which was filmed but never released due to a financial dispute.\n\n===Second reformation, death of Paul Baloff and ''Tempo of the Damned'' (2001\u20132004)===\nIn 2001, Exodus reformed once again with the 1997 lineup, initially to play the [[Chuck Billy (vocalist)|Chuck Billy]] and [[Chuck Schuldiner]] benefit [[Thrash of the Titans]] concert. There was talk of recording a new studio album and the band continued to play shows in and around the San Francisco Bay Area.\n\nHowever, on February 2, 2002, Paul Baloff died after suffering a stroke. Former vocalist Steve Souza was brought back into the band to finish the rest of their concert commitments. Although it appeared to outsiders that with Baloff's death Exodus would cease to exist, guitarist Gary Holt was determined to release a new studio album. The result was 2004's ''[[Tempo of the Damned]]'' released on [[Nuclear Blast Records]]. An oddity of the recording sessions was that one track, \"Crime of the Century\", was dropped under mysterious circumstances. The song chronicled Exodus's time under Century Media (of which Nuclear Blast is a subsidiary). Although it was publicly denied, rumors swirled that Century Media forced the song off the record. \"Crime of the Century\" was replaced with \"Impaler\", a song which was written when Kirk Hammett was still in the band, and was previously featured on the ''Another Lesson in Violence'' live record.\n\n===Feud with Steve Souza, new members and ''Shovel Headed Kill Machine'' (2004\u20132006)===\n[[File:Rob Dukes, Exodus 5.jpg|thumb|left|Vocalist [[Rob Dukes]] was one of three new members to join Exodus in 2005. He was part of the band until 2014.]]\nSteve Souza once again left the band due to business and personal differences in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/singer-zetro-souza-quits-exodus-again/ |title=Singer Zetro Souza Quits Exodus (Again) |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=September 13, 2004 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> This led to a feud between himself and Gary Holt, who subsequently issued a statement in which he was heavily critical of Souza, claiming he had suddenly left the band while on tour only a day before they were due to leave for a show in [[Mexico City]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exodus-guitarist-fat-ass-zetro-souza-is-human-crap/ |title=Exodus Guitarist: 'Fat Ass' Zetro Souza Is 'Human Crap' |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=September 13, 2004 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> [[Exhumed (band)|Exhumed]] frontman Matt Harvey filled in for the Mexico City date<ref>{{cite web|title=EXHUMED Frontman Says Singing For EXODUS In Mexico Was An 'Honor'|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exhumed-frontman-says-singing-for-exodus-in-mexico-was-an-honor/|website=Blabbermouth}}</ref> and Steev Esquivel (ex-[[Defiance (band)|Defiance]] and [[Skinlab]]) played on the fall South American dates.<ref>{{cite web|title=SKINLAB Singer To Front EXODUS On Rescheduled South American Tour|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/skinlab-singer-to-front-exodus-on-rescheduled-south-american-tour/|website=Blabbermouth}}</ref> The band eventually found a permanent replacement in Rob Dukes.\n\nIn 2005, Rick Hunolt left the band to focus on his family.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exodus-confirm-guitarist-rick-hunolt-s-departure/ |title=Exodus Confirm Guitarist Rick Hunolt's Departure |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=August 4, 2005 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> He was replaced by [[Heathen (band)|Heathen]] guitarist [[Lee Altus]]. Tom Hunting also took leave of the band following a re-occurrence of the nervous problems that led to his temporary departure in 1989. Hunting was replaced with [[Paul Bostaph]] who had previously played with [[Slayer]] and [[Testament (band)|Testament]]. The revamped line up released the album ''[[Shovel Headed Kill Machine]]'' in 2005. The tour for the album led to extensive travel of the US, Europe, and Japan, as well as their first-ever visit to Australia.\n\n===Reunion with Tom Hunting and the ''Exhibit'' albums (2007\u20132013)===\nTom Hunting returned to the band in March 2007 in time to record and release their 8th studio album ''[[The Atrocity Exhibition... Exhibit A]]''. They performed at the [[Wacken Open Air]] Festival in the summer of 2008. In April 2009, Exodus embarked on a co-headlining North American tour with [[Kreator]] and also featuring [[Belphegor (band)|Belphegor]], [[Warbringer]], and Epicurean. Exodus then went on tour supporting [[Arch Enemy]] along with [[Arsis]] and [[Mutiny Within]].\n\nExodus provided the voices of the customers at the Duncan Hills Coffee Shop and five of the sick people in [[Cartoon Network]]'s ''[[Metalocalypse]]''.\n\nExodus released a re-recording of their 1985 debut album ''Bonded by Blood'' entitled ''[[Let There Be Blood]]'' in 2008. Gary Holt released the following statement about the band's decision to revisit their debut album: \"After many years in the planning and discussion stage, we have finally completed the re-recording of 'Bonded By Blood'. We have decided to call it 'Let There Be Blood' and it is our way of paying homage to [late singer] Paul Baloff by showing how relevant these songs we had written together still are. We aren't trying to replace the original; that's impossible anyway. We are just giving these songs the benefit of modern production. It's something we talked about before Paul's death and it's always been important to us to do. We were super excited about entering the studio once again to record these classics, and now it's back to writing the next studio record!\"{{citation needed|date=December 2010}}\n\nThe album ''[[Exhibit B: The Human Condition]]'' was recorded in northern California with British producer Andy Sneap ([[Megadeth]], [[Arch Enemy]], [[Kreator]]) and released on Nuclear Blast Records in May 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=134987 |title=Exodus: New Album Pushed Back To May - Blabbermouth.net |website=Roadrunnerrecords.com |date=February 12, 2010 |accessdate=March 28, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606063706/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=134987 |archivedate=June 6, 2011}}</ref> It was announced in January 2010 that Exodus was to be on [[Megadeth]]'s ''[[Rust in Peace]]'' 20th Anniversary tour along with [[Testament (band)|Testament]]. Exodus was featured on the cover of Decibel magazine's June 2010 issue, with a feature article on them.\n\n[[File:W00148 HellFest2012 Exodus.JPG|thumb|Exodus at 2012 Hellfest. This was one of the band's first shows with former guitarist [[Rick Hunolt]] (far right) in seven years.]]\n[[File:Exodus Rockharz 2018 12.jpg|thumb|Guitarist Lee Altus at Rockharz Open Air 2018]]\n[[File:Exodus Rockharz 2018 26.jpg|thumb|Drummer Tom Hunting at Rockharz Open Air 2018]]\n\nExodus co-headlined with [[Kreator]], [[Suicidal Angels]] and [[Death Angel]] on the Thrashfest tour in late 2010 and were one of the headlining bands at Wacken Open Air 2011.\n\nExodus toured with [[Rob Zombie]] and [[Slayer]] in 2011 on their Hell on Earth tour as the opening act. Gary Holt filled in for Slayer guitarist [[Jeff Hanneman]] during the tour after Hanneman contracted [[necrotizing fasciitis]] caused by a spider bite.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=154594 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120909092313/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=154594 |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 9, 2012 |title=Slayer With Exodus Guitarist Gary Holt: First Video Footage From Soundwave Kick Off Show - Blabbermouth.net |website=Roadrunnerrecords.com |date=February 26, 2011 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> Holt filled in for Hanneman again on Slayer's next tour in the summer of 2012. When Exodus also toured in the summer of 2012, guitarist [[Rick Hunolt]] (who left Exodus in 2005) filled in for Holt. [[Cannibal Corpse]] guitarist [[Pat O'Brien (guitarist)|Pat O'Brien]] also filled in for Holt during this time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guitarworld.com/exodus-be-joined-former-guitarist-rick-hunolt-upcoming-tour-dates |title=Exodus to Be Joined By Former Guitarist Rick Hunolt on Upcoming Tour Dates |publisher=Guitar World |date=December 3, 2013 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> Since Hanneman's death, Holt has become his permanent replacement.\n\nOn February 4, 2012 a Paul Baloff Memorial Reunion Concert was held at the Oakland Metro Opera House. Former and current Exodus members in attendance included [[Kirk Hammett]], Rick Hunolt, [[Gary Holt (musician)|Gary Holt]], Geoff Andrews, [[Lee Altus]], [[Rob Dukes]], [[Tom Hunting]] and Jack Gibson. It was the first time they had all played together since 1983. The band was confirmed for the [[Graspop Metal Meeting|Graspop Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.bravewords.com/news/183256 |title=EXODUS \u2013 3-Guitar Attack Planned For Graspop Festival |website=Bravewords.com |date= |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> and for the [[Hellfest (French music festival)|Hellfest]] in June 2012. By the summer of 2012, Exodus had begun writing new material for their tenth studio album.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=176125 |title=Exodus Bassist On Randy Blythe Concert Incident: 'If You Come On Stage, You're Trespassing' |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=June 29, 2012 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=193189 |title=Exodus Taps Heathen Guitarist Kragen Lum For Select European Shows |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=July 31, 2013 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=179763 |title=Exodus Frontman Talks Next Album (Video) |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=September 21, 2012 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> On March 27, it was announced that the band entered the studio and were well into recording drum tracks, and the album was expected for a fall 2014 release.\n\n===Reunion with Steve Souza and ''Blood In, Blood Out'' (2014\u20132015)===\nOn June 8, 2014, Exodus announced that vocalist [[Rob Dukes]] had left the band,<ref name=\"blabbermouth1\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exodus-parts-ways-with-singer-rob-dukes/ |title=Exodus Parts Ways With Singer Rob Dukes, Welcomes Back Steve 'Zetro' Souza |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=June 8, 2014 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> and was replaced by [[Steve Souza|Steve \"Zetro\" Souza]], making this the second time he had rejoined the band.<ref name=\"blabbermouth1\"/> Souza recorded vocals on the new album; the band's first to feature him since 2004's ''[[Tempo of the Damned]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/steve-zetro-souza-to-begin-recording-vocals-for-new-exodus-album-this-week/ |title=Steve 'Zetro' Souza To Begin Recording Vocals For New Exodus Album This Week |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=June 9, 2014 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/steve-zetro-souza-a-lot-went-into-my-decision-to-rejoin-exodus/ |title=Steve 'Zetro' Souza: 'A Lot Went Into My Decision' To Rejoin Exodus |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=June 10, 2014 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> On June 26, 2014, Exodus announced on their official website that the album would be called ''[[Blood In, Blood Out (Exodus album)|Blood In, Blood Out]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Exodus Announces Exclusive VIP Packs for Upcoming Slayer Tour w/ Special Guests Suicidal Tendencies and Exodus|url=http://exodusattack.com/site/2014/06/26/exodus-announces-exclusive-vip-packs-for-upcoming-slayer-tour-w-special-guests-suicidal-tendencies-and-exodus/|website=Exodusattack.com|accessdate=June 29, 2014|date=June 26, 2014}}</ref> and it was released on October 14.<ref>{{cite web|title=Exodus To Release 'Blood In, Blood Out' Album In October|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exodus-to-release-blood-in-blood-out-album-in-october/|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=July 9, 2014|date=July 9, 2014}}</ref> ''Blood In, Blood Out'' received positive reviews from music critics upon its release, and peaked at {{abbr|No.|number}}&nbsp;38 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], making it the band's highest chart position so far.<ref>{{cite web|title=Exodus' 'Blood In Blood Out' Cracks U.S. Top 40|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exodus-blood-in-blood-out-cracks-u-s-top-40/|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=October 22, 2014|date=October 22, 2014}}</ref> [[Heathen (band)|Heathen]] Guitarist Kragen Lum was brought in to replace Gary Holt for several live dates while Holt performed and recorded with [[Slayer]].<ref>{{cite web|title=EXODUS Fill-In Guitarist KRAGEN LUM: 'They Treat Me Like Family'\n|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exodus-fill-in-guitarist-kragen-lum-they-treat-me-like-family/}}</ref>\n\nExodus performed at the Australian Soundwave Festival 2015, which was held across two weekends.<ref>{{cite web |author=|date=December 22, 2014 |title=Steel Panther, Exodus, Falling In Reverse, Etc. Added To 2015 'Soundwave Festival' |url=http://www.theprp.com/2014/12/22/news/steel-panther-exodus-falling-in-reverse-etc-added-to-2015-soundwave-festival/}}</ref> In April and May 2015, Exodus (along with [[Shattered Sun]]) supported [[Testament (band)|Testament]] on their ''[[Dark Roots of Thrash|Dark Roots of Thrash II]]'' tour.<ref>{{cite web|title=Testament And Exodus To Join Forces For 'Dark Roots Of Thrash II' Tour|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/testament-and-exodus-to-join-forces-for-dark-roots-of-thrash-ii-tour/|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|date=February 17, 2015|accessdate=February 17, 2015}}</ref> Exodus then toured around Europe in June, including two nights at the [[Camden Underworld|Underworld]] in London.\n\n===Upcoming eleventh studio album (2016\u2013present)===\nIn June 2016, Steve Souza said that the band's next studio album could be released in late 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/steve-zetro-souza-says-next-exodus-album-could-arrive-in-late-2017/|title=STEVE 'ZETRO' SOUZA Says Next EXODUS Album Could Arrive In Late 2017|publisher=Blabbermouth.net|accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/steve-zetro-souza-its-time-for-exodus-to-start-putting-some-new-music-together/|title=STEVE 'ZETRO' SOUZA: It's Time For EXODUS To Start Putting Some New Music Together|publisher=Blabbermouth.net|accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref> However, he stated that Exodus would enter the studio around October or November 2017 to begin recording the album for a March 2018 release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exodus-to-record-follow-up-to-blood-in-blood-out-in-the-fall/|title=EXODUS To Record Follow-Up To 'Blood In Blood Out' In The Fall|publisher=Blabbermouth.net|accessdate=May 5, 2017}}</ref> Drummer [[Tom Hunting]] said that the band had several songs written, with the rest of them in the works.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exodus-has-five-or-six-songs-written-for-next-album-says-tom-hunting/|title=EXODUS Has 'Five Or Six' Songs Written For Next Album, Says TOM HUNTING|publisher=Blabbermouth.net|accessdate=June 10, 2017}}</ref> Souza explained that the material does not sound like a continuation of ''Blood In, Blood Out'', but rather \"a lot of records put together, I think\", describing it as \"heavy as shit, though \u2014 really fucking heavy.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exoduss-next-album-will-be-heavy-as-st-says-steve-zetro-souza/|title=EXODUS's Next Album Will Be 'Heavy As S**t,' Says STEVE 'ZETRO' SOUZA|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=June 21, 2017}}</ref> He then stated that Exodus was in the process of writing their new album, with a set time period of entering the studio for late in the year or early 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exodus-singer-on-next-album-were-writing-right-now/|title=EXODUS Singer On Next Album: 'We're Writing Right Now'|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=August 29, 2017}}</ref> Hunting said that the album could include another collaboration with [[Kirk Hammett]] and a possible guest appearance by former guitarist [[Rick Hunolt]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exoduss-next-album-might-feature-guest-appearance-by-former-guitarist-rick-hunolt/|title=EXODUS's Next Album Might Feature Guest Appearance By Former Guitarist RICK HUNOLT|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=September 30, 2017}}</ref> Hunolt, Paul Bostaph and Rob Dukes joined the band on stage for a one-off reunion show in July 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exodus-rejoined-by-rob-dukes-rick-hunolt-paul-bostaph-at-san-francisco-concert-video/|title=EXODUS Rejoined By ROB DUKES, RICK HUNOLT, PAUL BOSTAPH At San Francisco Concert (Video)|date=July 9, 2017|publisher=}}</ref> On September 29, 2017, Exodus were confirmed to appear at the 2018 edition of the Rockharz Open Air in Germany as one of the early bands noted for the main stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://exodusattack.com/site/2017/09/29/exodus-confirmed-for-rockharz-open-air-2018/|title=Exodus confirmed for Rockharz Open Air 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a January 2018 interview with Jimmy Kay of Canada's The Metal Voice, Holt confirmed that the band was still writing songs for the next studio album.<ref>{{cite web|title=Will There Be A New SLAYER Studio Album? 'I'd Say It's A No,' Says GARY HOLT|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/will-there-be-a-new-slayer-studio-album-id-say-its-a-no-says-gary-holt/|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|date=January 25, 2018|accessdate=January 26, 2018}}</ref> Souza said that fans would have to wait until at least the end of 2019 for a new studio album, mainly due to Holt's involvement in Slayer's farewell tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalinsider.net/interviews/interview-exodus-steve-zetro-souza-talks-cartoons-mr-pickles-thrashtacular-tour|title=Interview: Exodus\u2019 Steve \"Zetro\" Souza talks cartoons, Mr. Pickles Thrashtacular tour, Exodus album update|author=El Prezidente|publisher=metalinsider.net|accessdate=February 22, 2018}}</ref> He then said that the new album would possibly be released in late 2019 or early 2020, promising that the album would be \"very violent and very heavy.\"<ref name=\"new album blabbermouth\" />\n\nExodus headlined the 2018 installment of the MTV Headbangers Ball European Tour, along with [[Death Angel]], [[Suicidal Angels]] and [[Sodom (band)|Sodom]] from late November to mid-December 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exodus-to-headline-european-mtv-headbangers-ball-tour/|title=EXODUS To Headline European 'MTV Headbangers Ball Tour'|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref> The band will also tour Europe with [[Testament (band)|Testament]] and Death Angel in February and March 2020 by taking part in [[The Bay Strikes Back]] tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/testament-exodus-and-death-angel-to-join-forces-for-the-bay-strikes-back-2020-european-tour/|title=TESTAMENT, EXODUS And DEATH ANGEL To Join Forces For 'The Bay Strikes Back 2020' European Tour|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=July 29, 2019|date=July 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Musical style, legacy and influences==\nExodus have been credited as one of the pioneers of the [[thrash metal]] genre, which achieved mainstream popularity in the 1980s and early 1990s,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goldenplec.com/live-reviews/exodus-in-the-button-factory-review/|title=Exodus in the Button Factory \u2013 Review \u2022 Live Review|publisher=goldenplec.com|date=August 15, 2013|accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://crypticrock.com/interview-steve-zetro-souza-of-exodus/|title=Interview \u2013 Steve \"Zetro\" Souza of Exodus|publisher=crypticrock.com|date=March 26, 2015|accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.downtownmagazinenyc.com/exodus-singer-steve-zetro-souza-talks-playstation-theater-shows-with-king-diamond-next-album-disney-and-more/|title=Exodus singer Steve \"Zetro\" Souza talks Playstation Theater shows with King Diamond, next album, Disney and more|publisher=downtownmagazinenyc.com|date=November 12, 2015|accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"fullinbloommusic.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fullinbloommusic.com/overkill-biography-dd-verni-blitz-ellsworth.html|title=Exodus \u2013 Biography \u2013 Bonded by Blood \u2013 Gary Holt \u2013 Paul Baloff \u2013 Kirk Hammett|website=fullinbloommusic.com|accessdate=January 26, 2015}}</ref> and is often credited as the first [[Bay Area thrash metal]] band to exist,<ref name=\"fullinbloommusic.com\"/> predating [[Metallica]], who were originally from Los Angeles. Exodus is also considered to be a member of the \"big eight\" of the genre, along with Metallica, [[Megadeth]], [[Slayer]], [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]], [[Testament (band)|Testament]], [[Overkill (band)|Overkill]] and [[Death Angel]].<ref name=\"da allmusic\"/>\n\nExodus' main influences include [[AC/DC]], [[Angel Witch]], [[Black Sabbath]], [[Deep Purple]], [[Diamond Head (English band)|Diamond Head]], [[Iron Maiden]], [[Judas Priest]], [[Led Zeppelin]], [[Mercyful Fate]], [[Mot\u00f6rhead]], [[Nazareth (band)|Nazareth]], [[Ted Nugent]], [[Rainbow (rock band)|Rainbow]], [[Sweet Savage]], [[Thin Lizzy]], [[Tygers of Pan Tang]], [[UFO (band)|UFO]], [[Van Halen]] and [[Venom (band)|Venom]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.getreadytorock.com/pure_metal/exodus.htm|title=Interview with Tom Hunting and Gary Holt of Thrash metal rock band Exodus|publisher=Get Ready to ROCK!|accessdate=January 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/steve-zetro-souza-bands-don-t-survive-off-record-sales-anymore/|title=Steve 'Zetro' Souza: Bands Don't Survive Off Record Sales Anymore|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|date=September 8, 2012|accessdate=January 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Loudwire|Loudwire.com]] placed Exodus at number five on its list of the 10 Best Thrash Bands of All Time, calling them \"The original kings of the Bay Area thrash scene\", and saying that \"While their uncompromising sound and uneven output in the coming decades kept world domination and platinum success ever at bay, you'd be hard passed to finger any other band, short of Slayer, perhaps, that's flown the thrash flag as proudly and unwaveringly as Exodus.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/best-thrash-metal-bands/|title=10 Best Thrash Metal Bands of All Time|publisher=[[Loudwire|Loudwire.com]]|date=August 15, 2013|accessdate=January 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt has been debated whether or not Exodus belongs in the \"Big Five\" of thrash metal with [[Metallica]], [[Megadeth]], [[Slayer]] and [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]], due to their involvement with the early 1980s thrash metal scene. [[VH1]] stated, \"Much is made of Thrash's Big Four: Metallica, Slayer, Megadeth, and Anthrax. True devotees know, however, that Big Five is the actual proper figure and that Exodus is the band that completes the quintet.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/25827/10-greatest-thrash-metal-debut-albums/|title=10 Greatest Thrash Metal Debut Albums Of All Time|publisher=[[VH1|VH1.com]]|date=June 11, 2015|accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref> Anthrax guitarist [[Scott Ian]] also stated that, \"People talk about the 'Big Four' all the time, but back then it was really the 'Big Five' because Exodus were just as important and just as influential as everybody else.\" Megadeth founder [[Dave Mustaine]] said in a 1990 interview that, to him, the \"Big Four\" were Exodus, Slayer, Metallica and Megadeth, adding that \"Exodus are a much better band \u2013 I really like Exodus. [[Gary Holt (musician)|Gary Holt]] and [[Rick Hunolt]] are really great guitar players. I like Scott Ian, but anyone else in that band kind of bores me. Having a disco thing is not what I think having a metal band is all about, and that guy had the audacity to say that he and I should together! I felt like saying what are you planning to do? Open a disco fashion shop?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://megadeth.rockmetal.art.pl/articles_hotmetal1990.html|title=The Big Four|publisher=megadeth.rockmetal.art.pl|date=September 1990|accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref> Along with Ian and Mustaine,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/anthrax-guitarist-says-expanded-big-four-should-include-exodus/|title=Anthrax Guitarist Says Expanded 'Big Four' Should Include Exodus|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|date=September 18, 2012|accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/dave-mustaine-says-exodus-would-have-been-most-qualified-candidate-for-expanded-big-four-2/|title=Dave Mustaine Says Exodus Would Have Been Most Qualified Candidate For Expanded 'Big Four'|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|date=July 6, 2013|accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref> Holt has agreed that Exodus should be included in the \"Big Five\" of thrash metal because they \"were there at the start of thrash metal with Metallica in the real early '80s. Same thing with Megadeth because Mustaine was a part of Metallica's birth and he also created Megadeth.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/gary-holt-says-big-four-should-be-expanded-to-include-exodus-we-were-there-at-the-start/|title=Gary Holt Says 'Big Four' Should be Expanded To Include Exodus: 'We Were There At The Start'|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|date=May 6, 2010|accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref> Frontman [[Steve Souza|Steve \"Zetro\" Souza]] has stated that the fact that Exodus was not included in the \"Big Four\" does not bother him, \"I've heard that term many times and it doesn't really matter to me. It's not the truth. There's them, and Overkill, Testament and Exodus. You could also talk about [[Kreator]], [[Sodom (band)|Sodom]] and [[Destruction (band)|Destruction]], if you want to get down to it. It doesn't bother me \u2014 I'm content where I'm at.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/steve-zetro-souza-isnt-bothered-by-exodus-not-being-part-of-big-four-it-doesnt-really-matter-to-me/|title=STEVE 'ZETRO' SOUZA Isn't Bothered By EXODUS Not Being Part Of 'Big Four': 'It Doesn't Really Matter To Me'|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|date=September 5, 2017|accessdate=September 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Band members==\n{{main|List of Exodus members}}\n'''Current members'''\n* [[Tom Hunting]] \u2013 drums (1979\u20131989, 1997\u20131998, 2001\u20132005, 2007\u2013present), lead vocals (1979\u20131982)\n* [[Gary Holt (musician)|Gary Holt]] \u2013 guitars, backing vocals (1981\u20131993, 1997\u20131998, 2001\u2013present)\n* [[Steve Souza|Steve \"Zetro\" Souza]] \u2013 lead vocals (1986\u20131993, 2002\u20132004, 2014\u2013present)\n* Jack Gibson \u2013 bass, backing vocals (1997\u20131998, 2001\u2013present)\n* [[Lee Altus]] \u2013 guitars (2005\u2013present)\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Exodus discography}}\n<!-- This section is for studio albums only; DO NOT add \"Let There Be Blood\", which is a compilation album despite the fact that it is a re-recording of \"Bonded by Blood\". All other releases (EPs, singles, etc.) are covered in the discography article and are not to be listed in this section. See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians/Article_guidelines#Discography_section-->\n* ''[[Bonded by Blood]]'' (1985)\n* ''[[Pleasures of the Flesh]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Fabulous Disaster]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Impact Is Imminent]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[Force of Habit]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Tempo of the Damned]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Shovel Headed Kill Machine]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[The Atrocity Exhibition... Exhibit A]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Exhibit B: The Human Condition]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Blood In, Blood Out (Exodus album)|Blood In, Blood Out]]'' (2014)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Exodus (band)|Exodus}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.exodusattack.com}}\n* [http://www.myspace.com/exodus Official MySpace page]\n* [http://www.metalfan.ro/articol.php?sectiune=2&id_doc=3166&lng=2 Exodus&nbsp;\u2013 Gary Holt interview @ Metalfan.ro&nbsp;\u2013 English]\n\n{{Exodus(band)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Exodus}}\n[[Category:1979 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1979]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 1994]]\n[[Category:Musical groups reestablished in 1997]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 1998]]\n[[Category:Musical groups reestablished in 2001]]\n[[Category:Musical quintets]]\n[[Category:Nuclear Blast artists]]\n[[Category:Political music]]\n[[Category:Thrash metal musical groups from California]]\n[[Category:Combat Records artists]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records artists]]\n[[Category:Century Media Records artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Exodus (band)|the progressive rock band|Exodus (Polish band)}}\n{{short description|American thrash metal band}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Exodus\n| image = Exodus 2016231161029 2016-08-18 Summer Breeze - Sven - 1D X II - 0567 - AK8I5470 mod.jpg\n| caption = Exodus performing at the [[Summer Breeze Open Air]] festival in 2016\n| image_size = \n| landscape = yes\n| background = group_or_band\n| alias = \n| origin = [[Richmond, California]], U.S.\n| genre = [[Thrash metal]]\n| years_active = {{flatlist|\n* 1979\u20131994\n* 1997\u20131998\n* 2001\u2013present}}\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n* [[Century Media Records|Century Media]]\n* [[Combat Records|Combat]]\n* [[Nuclear Blast]]}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[Heathen (band)|Heathen]]\n* [[Hatriot (band)|Hatriot]]\n* [[Blind Illusion]]\n* [[Metallica]]\n* [[Possessed (band)|Possessed]]\n* [[Testament (band)|Testament]]\n* [[Slayer]]\n* [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]]\n* [[Megadeth]]\n* [[White Zombie (band)|White Zombie]]\n* [[Generation Kill (band)|Generation Kill]]}}\n\nPower Chord\n| website = [http://www.exodusattack.com/ www.exodusattack.com]\n| current_members = <!--Do not change, members are listed in order of joining the band as per Wikipedia guidelines.-->[[Gary Holt (musician)|Gary Holt]]<br>Jack Gibson<br>[[Lee Altus]]<br>[[Tom Hunting]]<br>[[Steve Souza|Steve \"Zetro\" Souza]]\n| past_members = [[List of Exodus members]]\n}}\n\n'''Exodus''' is an American [[thrash metal]] band formed in 1979 in [[Richmond, California]].<ref name=\"Enter Night\">{{cite book |last = Wall |first = Mick |title = Enter Night: A Biography of Metallica (page 119) |publisher = [[St. Martin's Press]] |date = May 10, 2011 |isbn = 0-312-64989-4}}</ref> They have gone through numerous lineup changes, two extended hiatuses, and the deaths of two former band members. Their current lineup consists of guitarists [[Gary Holt (musician)|Gary Holt]] and [[Lee Altus]], bassist Jack Gibson, drummer [[Tom Hunting]], and lead vocalist [[Steve Souza|Steve \"Zetro\" Souza]]. Hunting is one of the original members, and departed from Exodus twice, in 1989 and 2004, but rejoined in 2007. Holt joined the band about two years after its formation, and is the only member of Exodus to appear on all their releases.\n\nSince its formation, Exodus has released ten studio albums, two live albums, one compilation album, and a [[Let There Be Blood|re-recording]] of their [[Bonded by Blood|first album]]. Along with [[Metallica]] (whose longtime lead guitarist [[Kirk Hammett]] was an original member of Exodus), they are often credited as pioneers of the [[Bay Area thrash metal]] scene,<ref>{{cite web|title=Exodus To Release 'Blood In, Blood Out' Album In October|url=http://www2.gibson.com/News-Lifestyle/Shared/2011/June/Gibson-Interview-Kirk-Hammett-of-Metallica.aspx|work=[[Gibson Guitar Corporation|gibson.com]]|date=June 5, 2011|accessdate=October 12, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617193212/http://www.gibson.com/News-Lifestyle/Shared/2011/June/Gibson-Interview-Kirk-Hammett-of-Metallica.aspx|archive-date=June 17, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Legendary metal band Exodus, formed in Richmond, set to release 10th studio album|url=http://richmondstandard.com/2014/09/legendary-metal-band-exodus-formed-richmond-set-release-10th-studio-album/|work=richmondstandard.com|date=September 24, 2014|accessdate=October 12, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141019021512/http://richmondstandard.com/2014/09/legendary-metal-band-exodus-formed-richmond-set-release-10th-studio-album/|archive-date=October 19, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and have sold over five million albums worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegauntlet.com/article/29011/Exodus-Announces-Hometown-Gig |title=Exodus Announces Hometown Gig \u2013 The Gauntlet Heavy Metal News |website=Thegauntlet.com |date=October 3, 2013 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> Exodus is also considered to be as one the \"big eight\" of thrash metal, along with Metallica, [[Megadeth]], [[Slayer]], [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]], [[Testament (band)|Testament]], [[Overkill (band)|Overkill]] and [[Death Angel]].<ref name=\"da allmusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/death-angel-mn0000230845/biography|title=Death Angel Biography & History|work=[[AllMusic|allmusic.com]]|accessdate=October 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.herald-dispatch.com/features_entertainment/the-v-club-to-host-san-fran-thrash-metal-unit/article_75cf0136-81e9-5735-ba08-f275df1aed4d.html|title=The V Club to host San Fran thrash metal unit Death Angel|publisher=herald-dispatch.com|accessdate=October 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/mycity/news/legendary-metal-band-testament-to-be-part-of-silence-festival-2019|title=My City - Legendary metal band, Testament to be part of Silence Festival 2019|publisher=[[Rep\u00fablica (newspaper)|myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com]]|accessdate=October 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://metaljacketmagazine.com/metaldays-2020-first-bands-confirmed/|title=MetalDays 2020: First bands confirmed!|publisher=metaljacketmagazine.com|accessdate=October 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloodbath.ro/rockstadt-extreme-fest-2019-la-final-28-000-de-participanti-in-cele-4-zile-de-festival-si-50-de-trupe-au-concertat-pe-doua-scene-principale/|title=Rockstadt Extreme Fest 2019 la final: 28.000 de participan\u021bi \u00een cele 4 zile de festival \u0219i 50 de trupe au concertat pe dou\u0103 scene principale!|publisher=bloodbath.ro|accessdate=October 15, 2019}}</ref> The band had particular success in the mid-to-late 1980s with their first three studio albums: ''[[Bonded by Blood]]'' (1985), ''[[Pleasures of the Flesh]]'' (1987) and ''[[Fabulous Disaster]]'' (1989). The critical praise given to ''Fabulous Disaster'' garnered attention from major labels, including [[Capitol Records]], with whom Exodus signed in 1989. The band released two more studio albums (''[[Impact Is Imminent]]'' in 1990 and ''[[Force of Habit]]'' in 1992) before disbanding in 1994. After temporarily reuniting in 1997\u20131998, Exodus reformed once again in 2001, and since then, they have released five more studio albums, the most recent being ''[[Blood In, Blood Out (Exodus album)|Blood In, Blood Out]]'' (2014). The band is currently writing a follow-up album, tentatively due for release in 2020.<ref name=\"new album blabbermouth\">{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exoduss-next-album-will-be-very-violent-and-very-heavy/|title=EXODUS's Next Album Will Be 'Very Violent And Very Heavy'|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|date=August 6, 2018|accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Formation and early years (1979\u20131983)===\n[[File:Gary Holt Slayer Kiev 03.JPG|thumb|right|Guitarist [[Gary Holt (musician)|Gary Holt]] has been a member of Exodus since 1981, and is the only member to have performed on all of the band's albums.]]\n\nThe initial lineup of Exodus was formed in the late 1970s by guitarists [[Kirk Hammett]] and Tim Agnello, drummer/vocalist [[Tom Hunting]], and vocalist Keith Stewart, while they attended high school together. The band added bass guitarist Carlton Melson in 1980, and the quintet began making a name for themselves playing backyard parties and various school functions. They played mostly cover songs in the vein of 1970s hard rock and [[New wave of British heavy metal]] (NWOBHM) acts but also developed some of their own original songs. Stewart soon left the band and Hunting became the band's sole vocalist for some time. Carlton Melson was replaced in 1981 by bass guitarist Geoff Andrews.<ref>{{cite web|title=Carlton Melson interview|url=http://pestwebzine.com/index/carlton_melson/0-1457}}</ref> Tim Agnello would also leave the group, moving to New York City and staying involved in the music industry as a guitar player, manager, and writer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tim Agnello interview|url=https://www.cmalliance.org/alife/you-can-call-me-al/}}</ref> This left Exodus to perform as a power trio until a replacement was found in Hammett's friend and Exodus roadie [[Gary Holt (musician)|Gary Holt]].<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gvMDgl0z_ZA|title = Exodus / Slayer's Gary Holt \u2013 Wikipedia: Fact or Fiction?|date = April 8, 2015|accessdate = November 18, 2015|website = YouTube|publisher = LoudWire|last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nAlso in 1981, Hammett met El Cerrito resident [[Paul Baloff]] at a North Berkeley house party, a friendship that was started \u2013 according to Hammett \u2013 by their shared admiration for punk rock and 1970s heavy metal music. Baloff became the band's lead vocalist and the quintet recorded a 3-track demo tape in 1982 consisting of the songs \"Whipping Queen\", \"Death and Domination\" and \"Warlord\", a release which would be Hammett's only recording with Exodus. The band's music began to incorporate elements of [[hardcore punk]] into their NWOBHM roots, and Exodus was considered a pioneer of the [[Bay Area thrash metal]] scene. In November 1982, Exodus opened a show at San Francisco's [[Old Waldorf]] venue for [[Metallica]],<ref>[http://www.encycmet.com/live/26.shtml ENCYCLOPEDIA METALLICA \u2013 Concert Info: San Francisco, Old Waldorf California Nov 29, 1982] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090604222532/http://encycmet.com/live/26.shtml |date=June 4, 2009}}</ref> a then-relatively unknown (and unsigned) band from Los Angeles. As the band began playing more shows in Bay Area clubs, they gained a large, fervent fan base known for their violent concert behavior.\n\nIn early 1983, Hammett left Exodus to join [[Metallica]] on the recommendation of manager / producer [[Mark Whitaker (record producer)|Mark Whitaker]], leaving Gary Holt to effectively take creative control of the band. Hammett was replaced short term by Mike Maung, followed by [[Evan McCaskey]], before the band finally found a permanent replacement in guitarist [[Rick Hunolt]]. Geoff Andrews also left to start an early incarnation of pioneering [[death metal]] band [[Possessed (band)|Possessed]], and was replaced by bass guitarist Rob McKillop.\n\nIn the spring of 1984, Exodus entered Turk Street Studios with producer [[Doug Piercy]] to record demos of songs that would later appear on their debut album. The band was signed to New York-based Torrid Records and Exodus prepared to enter [[Prairie Sun Recording Studios]] that summer.\n\n===''Bonded By Blood'' and rise in popularity (1984\u20131991)===\n[[File:Exodus Rockharz 2018 30.jpg|thumb|left|Vocalist [[Steve Souza|Steve \"Zetro\" Souza]], who replaced [[Paul Baloff]], was a member of Exodus from 1986 to their first breakup in 1994, and again from 2002 to 2004. He rejoined the band once again in 2014.]]\nThe band recorded their first album, ''[[Bonded by Blood]]'', in the summer of 1984 with the band's manager [[Mark Whitaker (music producer)|Mark Whitaker]] producing. 1984 concert photos from Exodus shows at [[Aquatic Park (Berkeley)|Aquatic Park]]'s Eastern Front Metal Festival (with [[Slayer]] and [[Suicidal Tendencies]]) and [[Bay Area thrash metal#Ruthie's Inn, Berkeley|Ruthie's Inn]] (with [[Megadeth]] and Slayer) were included on the album sleeve inserts. Originally titled ''A Lesson in Violence'', the album was not released until April 1985 amidst creative and business setbacks. Whilst ''Bonded By Blood'' is considered a highly influential [[thrash metal]] album today, critics have regarded the delay in its release as having hindered the impact the album could have had. As Allmusic reviewer Eduardo Rivadavia would later write in his review for the album: \"Had it been released immediately after it was recorded in 1984, Exodus' ''Bonded by Blood'' might be regarded today alongside [[Metallica]]'s ''[[Kill 'Em All]]'' as one of the landmark albums responsible for launching the thrash metal wave.\"<ref name=allmusic>{{cite web|author=Eduardo Rivadavia |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/bonded-by-blood-mw0000192933 |title=Bonded by Blood \u2013 Exodus &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |date= |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> Exodus promoted the album by going on tour with [[Venom (band)|Venom]] and [[Slayer]]. Four songs from their performance of April 5, 1985 at Studio 54 in New York City were filmed and released on home video as ''Combat Tour Live: The Ultimate Revenge''. The band subsequently toured or played selected shows with bands like [[Exciter (band)|Exciter]], [[Megadeth]], [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]], [[King Diamond (band)|King Diamond]], [[Possessed (band)|Possessed]], [[Dirty Rotten Imbeciles|D.R.I.]], [[Nuclear Assault]] and [[Hirax]].\n\nShortly after touring for ''Bonded by Blood'' was complete, Paul Baloff was fired from the band allegedly due to his behavior related to alcohol and substance abuse, and was replaced by [[Steve Souza|Steve \"Zetro\" Souza]], who had previously been the lead vocalist for Legacy, an early incarnation of fellow Bay Area thrashers [[Testament (band)|Testament]]. Baloff went on to form the band Piranha in 1987.\n\nExodus' line-up remained stable for the recording of their next two albums, and the underground success attained with ''Bonded by Blood'' would lead to the group's signing to [[Sony Music|Sony]]/[[Combat Records]], who released the band's second effort ''[[Pleasures of the Flesh]]'' in 1987. The album was engineered by then-unknown [[Sylvia Massy]], who would go on to produce two releases by progressive metal band [[Tool (band)|Tool]]. In support of ''Pleasures of the Flesh'', Exodus toured with the likes of [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]], [[Celtic Frost]], [[M.O.D.]], [[L\u0227\u0227z Rockit]] and [[Testament (band)|Testament]].\n\n''[[Fabulous Disaster]]'', the group's third full-length album, was released in 1989. A [[music video]] for the song \"[[The Toxic Waltz (song)|The Toxic Waltz]]\" would receive consistent rotation on [[MTV]]'s ''[[Headbangers Ball]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.revolvermag.com/magazine/article/the-history-of-american-thrash |title=The History of American Thrash |publisher=[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver.com]] |accessdate=September 19, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125083043/http://www.revolvermag.com/magazine/article/the-history-of-american-thrash |archivedate=November 25, 2010}}</ref> While promoting ''Fabulous Disaster'', Exodus embarked on the [[Headbangers Ball Tour|Headbangers Ball]] tour with [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]] and [[Helloween]], which brought the band to a wider audience.\n\nAfter the success of ''Fabulous Disaster'', Exodus signed to [[Capitol Records]] in 1989, who released the band's fourth album ''[[Impact is Imminent]]'' the following year. Prior to recording the album, Tom Hunting left the band for personal reasons; he was replaced by [[John Tempesta]] on drums. In 1991, the band released their first live album, ''[[Good Friendly Violent Fun]]'', which was recorded during their 1989 tour.\n\n===''Force of Habit'', hiatus, and temporary reunion (1991\u20132000)===\n[[File:Exodus Rockharz 2018 33.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Jack Gibson joined Exodus in 1997 as bass guitarist and has been with the group ever since.]]\n\nAfter the release of ''Good Friendly Violent Fun'', the band toured sporadically for a year. Bass guitarist McKillop was replaced by Michael Butler before the group recorded and released their next studio album titled ''[[Force of Habit]]'' in 1992. This album was something of a departure from the band's signature sound, containing several slower, \"heavier\" songs with less emphasis on the thrash aspect of their older material. The 11-minute song \"Architect of Pain\" is a good example of the change of direction, having a much slower, grinding feel than the usual high tempo thrash they had become known for. After touring for ''Force of Habit'' was completed, behind-the-scenes issues as well as a changing musical environment prompted the band to split up.\n\nHolt and Hunting formed the groove / thrash metal outfit Wardance in the mid 90's playing several shows around the Bay Area and recording a 4-song demo, but the group never gained momentum and eventually disbanded.\n\nHolt and Hunting reunited with Paul Baloff and Rick Hunolt for a short Exodus tour in 1997. The lineup was completed with Wardance bassist Jack Gibson. They released a live album titled ''[[Another Lesson in Violence]]'' recorded at the [[Trocadero Transfer]] in front of a home town audience. However, the group disbanded again the following year, in part due to a falling out with record label Century Media over the way promotion for the live album was handled, and over an aborted attempt at a live concert video which was filmed but never released due to a financial dispute.\n\n===Second reformation, death of Paul Baloff and ''Tempo of the Damned'' (2001\u20132004)===\nIn 2001, Exodus reformed once again with the 1997 lineup, initially to play the [[Chuck Billy (vocalist)|Chuck Billy]] and [[Chuck Schuldiner]] benefit [[Thrash of the Titans]] concert. There was talk of recording a new studio album and the band continued to play shows in and around the San Francisco Bay Area.\n\nHowever, on February 2, 2002, Paul Baloff died after suffering a stroke. Former vocalist Steve Souza was brought back into the band to finish the rest of their concert commitments. Although it appeared to outsiders that with Baloff's death Exodus would cease to exist, guitarist Gary Holt was determined to release a new studio album. The result was 2004's ''[[Tempo of the Damned]]'' released on [[Nuclear Blast Records]]. An oddity of the recording sessions was that one track, \"Crime of the Century\", was dropped under mysterious circumstances. The song chronicled Exodus's time under Century Media (of which Nuclear Blast is a subsidiary). Although it was publicly denied, rumors swirled that Century Media forced the song off the record. \"Crime of the Century\" was replaced with \"Impaler\", a song which was written when Kirk Hammett was still in the band, and was previously featured on the ''Another Lesson in Violence'' live record.\n\n===Feud with Steve Souza, new members and ''Shovel Headed Kill Machine'' (2004\u20132006)===\n[[File:Rob Dukes, Exodus 5.jpg|thumb|left|Vocalist [[Rob Dukes]] was one of three new members to join Exodus in 2005. He was part of the band until 2014.]]\nSteve Souza once again left the band due to business and personal differences in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/singer-zetro-souza-quits-exodus-again/ |title=Singer Zetro Souza Quits Exodus (Again) |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=September 13, 2004 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> This led to a feud between himself and Gary Holt, who subsequently issued a statement in which he was heavily critical of Souza, claiming he had suddenly left the band while on tour only a day before they were due to leave for a show in [[Mexico City]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exodus-guitarist-fat-ass-zetro-souza-is-human-crap/ |title=Exodus Guitarist: 'Fat Ass' Zetro Souza Is 'Human Crap' |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=September 13, 2004 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> [[Exhumed (band)|Exhumed]] frontman Matt Harvey filled in for the Mexico City date<ref>{{cite web|title=EXHUMED Frontman Says Singing For EXODUS In Mexico Was An 'Honor'|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exhumed-frontman-says-singing-for-exodus-in-mexico-was-an-honor/|website=Blabbermouth}}</ref> and Steev Esquivel (ex-[[Defiance (band)|Defiance]] and [[Skinlab]]) played on the fall South American dates.<ref>{{cite web|title=SKINLAB Singer To Front EXODUS On Rescheduled South American Tour|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/skinlab-singer-to-front-exodus-on-rescheduled-south-american-tour/|website=Blabbermouth}}</ref> The band eventually found a permanent replacement in Rob Dukes.\n\nIn 2005, Rick Hunolt left the band to focus on his family.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exodus-confirm-guitarist-rick-hunolt-s-departure/ |title=Exodus Confirm Guitarist Rick Hunolt's Departure |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=August 4, 2005 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> He was replaced by [[Heathen (band)|Heathen]] guitarist [[Lee Altus]]. Tom Hunting also took leave of the band following a re-occurrence of the nervous problems that led to his temporary departure in 1989. Hunting was replaced with [[Paul Bostaph]] who had previously played with [[Slayer]] and [[Testament (band)|Testament]]. The revamped line up released the album ''[[Shovel Headed Kill Machine]]'' in 2005. The tour for the album led to extensive travel of the US, Europe, and Japan, as well as their first-ever visit to Australia.\n\n===Reunion with Tom Hunting and the ''Exhibit'' albums (2007\u20132013)===\nTom Hunting returned to the band in March 2007 in time to record and release their 8th studio album ''[[The Atrocity Exhibition... Exhibit A]]''. They performed at the [[Wacken Open Air]] Festival in the summer of 2008. In April 2009, Exodus embarked on a co-headlining North American tour with [[Kreator]] and also featuring [[Belphegor (band)|Belphegor]], [[Warbringer]], and Epicurean. Exodus then went on tour supporting [[Arch Enemy]] along with [[Arsis]] and [[Mutiny Within]].\n\nExodus provided the voices of the customers at the Duncan Hills Coffee Shop and five of the sick people in [[Cartoon Network]]'s ''[[Metalocalypse]]''.\n\nExodus released a re-recording of their 1985 debut album ''Bonded by Blood'' entitled ''[[Let There Be Blood]]'' in 2008. Gary Holt released the following statement about the band's decision to revisit their debut album: \"After many years in the planning and discussion stage, we have finally completed the re-recording of 'Bonded By Blood'. We have decided to call it 'Let There Be Blood' and it is our way of paying homage to [late singer] Paul Baloff by showing how relevant these songs we had written together still are. We aren't trying to replace the original; that's impossible anyway. We are just giving these songs the benefit of modern production. It's something we talked about before Paul's death and it's always been important to us to do. We were super excited about entering the studio once again to record these classics, and now it's back to writing the next studio record!\"{{citation needed|date=December 2010}}\n\nThe album ''[[Exhibit B: The Human Condition]]'' was recorded in northern California with British producer Andy Sneap ([[Megadeth]], [[Arch Enemy]], [[Kreator]]) and released on Nuclear Blast Records in May 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=134987 |title=Exodus: New Album Pushed Back To May - Blabbermouth.net |website=Roadrunnerrecords.com |date=February 12, 2010 |accessdate=March 28, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606063706/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=134987 |archivedate=June 6, 2011}}</ref> It was announced in January 2010 that Exodus was to be on [[Megadeth]]'s ''[[Rust in Peace]]'' 20th Anniversary tour along with [[Testament (band)|Testament]]. Exodus was featured on the cover of Decibel magazine's June 2010 issue, with a feature article on them.\n\n[[File:W00148 HellFest2012 Exodus.JPG|thumb|Exodus at 2012 Hellfest. This was one of the band's first shows with former guitarist [[Rick Hunolt]] (far right) in seven years.]]\n[[File:Exodus Rockharz 2018 12.jpg|thumb|Guitarist Lee Altus at Rockharz Open Air 2018]]\n[[File:Exodus Rockharz 2018 26.jpg|thumb|Drummer Tom Hunting at Rockharz Open Air 2018]]\n\nExodus co-headlined with [[Kreator]], [[Suicidal Angels]] and [[Death Angel]] on the Thrashfest tour in late 2010 and were one of the headlining bands at Wacken Open Air 2011.\n\nExodus toured with [[Rob Zombie]] and [[Slayer]] in 2011 on their Hell on Earth tour as the opening act. Gary Holt filled in for Slayer guitarist [[Jeff Hanneman]] during the tour after Hanneman contracted [[necrotizing fasciitis]] caused by a spider bite.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=154594 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120909092313/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=154594 |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 9, 2012 |title=Slayer With Exodus Guitarist Gary Holt: First Video Footage From Soundwave Kick Off Show - Blabbermouth.net |website=Roadrunnerrecords.com |date=February 26, 2011 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> Holt filled in for Hanneman again on Slayer's next tour in the summer of 2012. When Exodus also toured in the summer of 2012, guitarist [[Rick Hunolt]] (who left Exodus in 2005) filled in for Holt. [[Cannibal Corpse]] guitarist [[Pat O'Brien (guitarist)|Pat O'Brien]] also filled in for Holt during this time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guitarworld.com/exodus-be-joined-former-guitarist-rick-hunolt-upcoming-tour-dates |title=Exodus to Be Joined By Former Guitarist Rick Hunolt on Upcoming Tour Dates |publisher=Guitar World |date=December 3, 2013 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> Since Hanneman's death, Holt has become his permanent replacement.\n\nOn February 4, 2012 a Paul Baloff Memorial Reunion Concert was held at the Oakland Metro Opera House. Former and current Exodus members in attendance included [[Kirk Hammett]], Rick Hunolt, [[Gary Holt (musician)|Gary Holt]], Geoff Andrews, [[Lee Altus]], [[Rob Dukes]], [[Tom Hunting]] and Jack Gibson. It was the first time they had all played together since 1983. The band was confirmed for the [[Graspop Metal Meeting|Graspop Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.bravewords.com/news/183256 |title=EXODUS \u2013 3-Guitar Attack Planned For Graspop Festival |website=Bravewords.com |date= |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> and for the [[Hellfest (French music festival)|Hellfest]] in June 2012. By the summer of 2012, Exodus had begun writing new material for their tenth studio album.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=176125 |title=Exodus Bassist On Randy Blythe Concert Incident: 'If You Come On Stage, You're Trespassing' |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=June 29, 2012 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=193189 |title=Exodus Taps Heathen Guitarist Kragen Lum For Select European Shows |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=July 31, 2013 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=179763 |title=Exodus Frontman Talks Next Album (Video) |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=September 21, 2012 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> On March 27, it was announced that the band entered the studio and were well into recording drum tracks, and the album was expected for a fall 2014 release.\n\n===Reunion with Steve Souza and ''Blood In, Blood Out'' (2014\u20132015)===\nOn June 8, 2014, Exodus announced that vocalist [[Rob Dukes]] had left the band,<ref name=\"blabbermouth1\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exodus-parts-ways-with-singer-rob-dukes/ |title=Exodus Parts Ways With Singer Rob Dukes, Welcomes Back Steve 'Zetro' Souza |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=June 8, 2014 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> and was replaced by [[Steve Souza|Steve \"Zetro\" Souza]], making this the second time he had rejoined the band.<ref name=\"blabbermouth1\"/> Souza recorded vocals on the new album; the band's first to feature him since 2004's ''[[Tempo of the Damned]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/steve-zetro-souza-to-begin-recording-vocals-for-new-exodus-album-this-week/ |title=Steve 'Zetro' Souza To Begin Recording Vocals For New Exodus Album This Week |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=June 9, 2014 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/steve-zetro-souza-a-lot-went-into-my-decision-to-rejoin-exodus/ |title=Steve 'Zetro' Souza: 'A Lot Went Into My Decision' To Rejoin Exodus |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=June 10, 2014 |accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> On June 26, 2014, Exodus announced on their official website that the album would be called ''[[Blood In, Blood Out (Exodus album)|Blood In, Blood Out]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Exodus Announces Exclusive VIP Packs for Upcoming Slayer Tour w/ Special Guests Suicidal Tendencies and Exodus|url=http://exodusattack.com/site/2014/06/26/exodus-announces-exclusive-vip-packs-for-upcoming-slayer-tour-w-special-guests-suicidal-tendencies-and-exodus/|website=Exodusattack.com|accessdate=June 29, 2014|date=June 26, 2014}}</ref> and it was released on October 14.<ref>{{cite web|title=Exodus To Release 'Blood In, Blood Out' Album In October|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exodus-to-release-blood-in-blood-out-album-in-october/|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=July 9, 2014|date=July 9, 2014}}</ref> ''Blood In, Blood Out'' received positive reviews from music critics upon its release, and peaked at {{abbr|No.|number}}&nbsp;38 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], making it the band's highest chart position so far.<ref>{{cite web|title=Exodus' 'Blood In Blood Out' Cracks U.S. Top 40|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exodus-blood-in-blood-out-cracks-u-s-top-40/|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=October 22, 2014|date=October 22, 2014}}</ref> [[Heathen (band)|Heathen]] Guitarist Kragen Lum was brought in to replace Gary Holt for several live dates while Holt performed and recorded with [[Slayer]].<ref>{{cite web|title=EXODUS Fill-In Guitarist KRAGEN LUM: 'They Treat Me Like Family'\n|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exodus-fill-in-guitarist-kragen-lum-they-treat-me-like-family/}}</ref>\n\nExodus performed at the Australian Soundwave Festival 2015, which was held across two weekends.<ref>{{cite web |author=|date=December 22, 2014 |title=Steel Panther, Exodus, Falling In Reverse, Etc. Added To 2015 'Soundwave Festival' |url=http://www.theprp.com/2014/12/22/news/steel-panther-exodus-falling-in-reverse-etc-added-to-2015-soundwave-festival/}}</ref> In April and May 2015, Exodus (along with [[Shattered Sun]]) supported [[Testament (band)|Testament]] on their ''[[Dark Roots of Thrash|Dark Roots of Thrash II]]'' tour.<ref>{{cite web|title=Testament And Exodus To Join Forces For 'Dark Roots Of Thrash II' Tour|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/testament-and-exodus-to-join-forces-for-dark-roots-of-thrash-ii-tour/|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|date=February 17, 2015|accessdate=February 17, 2015}}</ref> Exodus then toured around Europe in June, including two nights at the [[Camden Underworld|Underworld]] in London.\n\n===Upcoming eleventh studio album (2016\u2013present)===\nIn June 2016, Steve Souza said that the band's next studio album could be released in late 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/steve-zetro-souza-says-next-exodus-album-could-arrive-in-late-2017/|title=STEVE 'ZETRO' SOUZA Says Next EXODUS Album Could Arrive In Late 2017|publisher=Blabbermouth.net|accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/steve-zetro-souza-its-time-for-exodus-to-start-putting-some-new-music-together/|title=STEVE 'ZETRO' SOUZA: It's Time For EXODUS To Start Putting Some New Music Together|publisher=Blabbermouth.net|accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref> However, he stated that Exodus would enter the studio around October or November 2017 to begin recording the album for a March 2018 release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exodus-to-record-follow-up-to-blood-in-blood-out-in-the-fall/|title=EXODUS To Record Follow-Up To 'Blood In Blood Out' In The Fall|publisher=Blabbermouth.net|accessdate=May 5, 2017}}</ref> Drummer [[Tom Hunting]] said that the band had several songs written, with the rest of them in the works.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exodus-has-five-or-six-songs-written-for-next-album-says-tom-hunting/|title=EXODUS Has 'Five Or Six' Songs Written For Next Album, Says TOM HUNTING|publisher=Blabbermouth.net|accessdate=June 10, 2017}}</ref> Souza explained that the material does not sound like a continuation of ''Blood In, Blood Out'', but rather \"a lot of records put together, I think\", describing it as \"heavy as shit, though \u2014 really fucking heavy.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exoduss-next-album-will-be-heavy-as-st-says-steve-zetro-souza/|title=EXODUS's Next Album Will Be 'Heavy As S**t,' Says STEVE 'ZETRO' SOUZA|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=June 21, 2017}}</ref> He then stated that Exodus was in the process of writing their new album, with a set time period of entering the studio for late in the year or early 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exodus-singer-on-next-album-were-writing-right-now/|title=EXODUS Singer On Next Album: 'We're Writing Right Now'|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=August 29, 2017}}</ref> Hunting said that the album could include another collaboration with [[Kirk Hammett]] and a possible guest appearance by former guitarist [[Rick Hunolt]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exoduss-next-album-might-feature-guest-appearance-by-former-guitarist-rick-hunolt/|title=EXODUS's Next Album Might Feature Guest Appearance By Former Guitarist RICK HUNOLT|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=September 30, 2017}}</ref> Hunolt, Paul Bostaph and Rob Dukes joined the band on stage for a one-off reunion show in July 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exodus-rejoined-by-rob-dukes-rick-hunolt-paul-bostaph-at-san-francisco-concert-video/|title=EXODUS Rejoined By ROB DUKES, RICK HUNOLT, PAUL BOSTAPH At San Francisco Concert (Video)|date=July 9, 2017|publisher=}}</ref> On September 29, 2017, Exodus were confirmed to appear at the 2018 edition of the Rockharz Open Air in Germany as one of the early bands noted for the main stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://exodusattack.com/site/2017/09/29/exodus-confirmed-for-rockharz-open-air-2018/|title=Exodus confirmed for Rockharz Open Air 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a January 2018 interview with Jimmy Kay of Canada's The Metal Voice, Holt confirmed that the band was still writing songs for the next studio album.<ref>{{cite web|title=Will There Be A New SLAYER Studio Album? 'I'd Say It's A No,' Says GARY HOLT|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/will-there-be-a-new-slayer-studio-album-id-say-its-a-no-says-gary-holt/|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|date=January 25, 2018|accessdate=January 26, 2018}}</ref> Souza said that fans would have to wait until at least the end of 2019 for a new studio album, mainly due to Holt's involvement in Slayer's farewell tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalinsider.net/interviews/interview-exodus-steve-zetro-souza-talks-cartoons-mr-pickles-thrashtacular-tour|title=Interview: Exodus\u2019 Steve \"Zetro\" Souza talks cartoons, Mr. Pickles Thrashtacular tour, Exodus album update|author=El Prezidente|publisher=metalinsider.net|accessdate=February 22, 2018}}</ref> He then said that the new album would possibly be released in late 2019 or early 2020, promising that the album would be \"very violent and very heavy.\"<ref name=\"new album blabbermouth\" />\n\nExodus headlined the 2018 installment of the MTV Headbangers Ball European Tour, along with [[Death Angel]], [[Suicidal Angels]] and [[Sodom (band)|Sodom]] from late November to mid-December 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/exodus-to-headline-european-mtv-headbangers-ball-tour/|title=EXODUS To Headline European 'MTV Headbangers Ball Tour'|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref> The band will also tour Europe with [[Testament (band)|Testament]] and Death Angel in February and March 2020 by taking part in [[The Bay Strikes Back]] tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/testament-exodus-and-death-angel-to-join-forces-for-the-bay-strikes-back-2020-european-tour/|title=TESTAMENT, EXODUS And DEATH ANGEL To Join Forces For 'The Bay Strikes Back 2020' European Tour|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=July 29, 2019|date=July 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Musical style, legacy and influences==\nExodus have been credited as one of the pioneers of the [[thrash metal]] genre, which achieved mainstream popularity in the 1980s and early 1990s,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goldenplec.com/live-reviews/exodus-in-the-button-factory-review/|title=Exodus in the Button Factory \u2013 Review \u2022 Live Review|publisher=goldenplec.com|date=August 15, 2013|accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://crypticrock.com/interview-steve-zetro-souza-of-exodus/|title=Interview \u2013 Steve \"Zetro\" Souza of Exodus|publisher=crypticrock.com|date=March 26, 2015|accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.downtownmagazinenyc.com/exodus-singer-steve-zetro-souza-talks-playstation-theater-shows-with-king-diamond-next-album-disney-and-more/|title=Exodus singer Steve \"Zetro\" Souza talks Playstation Theater shows with King Diamond, next album, Disney and more|publisher=downtownmagazinenyc.com|date=November 12, 2015|accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"fullinbloommusic.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fullinbloommusic.com/overkill-biography-dd-verni-blitz-ellsworth.html|title=Exodus \u2013 Biography \u2013 Bonded by Blood \u2013 Gary Holt \u2013 Paul Baloff \u2013 Kirk Hammett|website=fullinbloommusic.com|accessdate=January 26, 2015}}</ref> and is often credited as the first [[Bay Area thrash metal]] band to exist,<ref name=\"fullinbloommusic.com\"/> predating [[Metallica]], who were originally from Los Angeles. Exodus is also considered to be a member of the \"big eight\" of the genre, along with Metallica, [[Megadeth]], [[Slayer]], [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]], [[Testament (band)|Testament]], [[Overkill (band)|Overkill]] and [[Death Angel]].<ref name=\"da allmusic\"/>\n\nExodus' main influences include [[AC/DC]], [[Angel Witch]], [[Black Sabbath]], [[Deep Purple]], [[Diamond Head (English band)|Diamond Head]], [[Iron Maiden]], [[Judas Priest]], [[Led Zeppelin]], [[Mercyful Fate]], [[Mot\u00f6rhead]], [[Nazareth (band)|Nazareth]], [[Ted Nugent]], [[Rainbow (rock band)|Rainbow]], [[Sweet Savage]], [[Thin Lizzy]], [[Tygers of Pan Tang]], [[UFO (band)|UFO]], [[Van Halen]] and [[Venom (band)|Venom]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.getreadytorock.com/pure_metal/exodus.htm|title=Interview with Tom Hunting and Gary Holt of Thrash metal rock band Exodus|publisher=Get Ready to ROCK!|accessdate=January 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/steve-zetro-souza-bands-don-t-survive-off-record-sales-anymore/|title=Steve 'Zetro' Souza: Bands Don't Survive Off Record Sales Anymore|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|date=September 8, 2012|accessdate=January 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Loudwire|Loudwire.com]] placed Exodus at number five on its list of the 10 Best Thrash Bands of All Time, calling them \"The original kings of the Bay Area thrash scene\", and saying that \"While their uncompromising sound and uneven output in the coming decades kept world domination and platinum success ever at bay, you'd be hard passed to finger any other band, short of Slayer, perhaps, that's flown the thrash flag as proudly and unwaveringly as Exodus.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/best-thrash-metal-bands/|title=10 Best Thrash Metal Bands of All Time|publisher=[[Loudwire|Loudwire.com]]|date=August 15, 2013|accessdate=January 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt has been debated whether or not Exodus belongs in the \"Big Five\" of thrash metal with [[Metallica]], [[Megadeth]], [[Slayer]] and [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]], due to their involvement with the early 1980s thrash metal scene. [[VH1]] stated, \"Much is made of Thrash's Big Four: Metallica, Slayer, Megadeth, and Anthrax. True devotees know, however, that Big Five is the actual proper figure and that Exodus is the band that completes the quintet.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/25827/10-greatest-thrash-metal-debut-albums/|title=10 Greatest Thrash Metal Debut Albums Of All Time|publisher=[[VH1|VH1.com]]|date=June 11, 2015|accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref> Anthrax guitarist [[Scott Ian]] also stated that, \"People talk about the 'Big Four' all the time, but back then it was really the 'Big Five' because Exodus were just as important and just as influential as everybody else.\" Megadeth founder [[Dave Mustaine]] said in a 1990 interview that, to him, the \"Big Four\" were Exodus, Slayer, Metallica and Megadeth, adding that \"Exodus are a much better band \u2013 I really like Exodus. [[Gary Holt (musician)|Gary Holt]] and [[Rick Hunolt]] are really great guitar players. I like Scott Ian, but anyone else in that band kind of bores me. Having a disco thing is not what I think having a metal band is all about, and that guy had the audacity to say that he and I should together! I felt like saying what are you planning to do? Open a disco fashion shop?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://megadeth.rockmetal.art.pl/articles_hotmetal1990.html|title=The Big Four|publisher=megadeth.rockmetal.art.pl|date=September 1990|accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref> Along with Ian and Mustaine,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/anthrax-guitarist-says-expanded-big-four-should-include-exodus/|title=Anthrax Guitarist Says Expanded 'Big Four' Should Include Exodus|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|date=September 18, 2012|accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/dave-mustaine-says-exodus-would-have-been-most-qualified-candidate-for-expanded-big-four-2/|title=Dave Mustaine Says Exodus Would Have Been Most Qualified Candidate For Expanded 'Big Four'|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|date=July 6, 2013|accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref> Holt has agreed that Exodus should be included in the \"Big Five\" of thrash metal because they \"were there at the start of thrash metal with Metallica in the real early '80s. Same thing with Megadeth because Mustaine was a part of Metallica's birth and he also created Megadeth.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/gary-holt-says-big-four-should-be-expanded-to-include-exodus-we-were-there-at-the-start/|title=Gary Holt Says 'Big Four' Should be Expanded To Include Exodus: 'We Were There At The Start'|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|date=May 6, 2010|accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref> Frontman [[Steve Souza|Steve \"Zetro\" Souza]] has stated that the fact that Exodus was not included in the \"Big Four\" does not bother him, \"I've heard that term many times and it doesn't really matter to me. It's not the truth. There's them, and Overkill, Testament and Exodus. You could also talk about [[Kreator]], [[Sodom (band)|Sodom]] and [[Destruction (band)|Destruction]], if you want to get down to it. It doesn't bother me \u2014 I'm content where I'm at.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/steve-zetro-souza-isnt-bothered-by-exodus-not-being-part-of-big-four-it-doesnt-really-matter-to-me/|title=STEVE 'ZETRO' SOUZA Isn't Bothered By EXODUS Not Being Part Of 'Big Four': 'It Doesn't Really Matter To Me'|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|date=September 5, 2017|accessdate=September 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Band members==\n{{main|List of Exodus members}}\n'''Current members'''\n* [[Tom Hunting]] \u2013 drums (1979\u20131989, 1997\u20131998, 2001\u20132005, 2007\u2013present), lead vocals (1979\u20131982)\n* [[Gary Holt (musician)|Gary Holt]] \u2013 guitars, backing vocals (1981\u20131993, 1997\u20131998, 2001\u2013present)\n* [[Steve Souza|Steve \"Zetro\" Souza]] \u2013 lead vocals (1986\u20131993, 2002\u20132004, 2014\u2013present)\n* Jack Gibson \u2013 bass, backing vocals (1997\u20131998, 2001\u2013present)\n* [[Lee Altus]] \u2013 guitars (2005\u2013present)\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Exodus discography}}\n<!-- This section is for studio albums only; DO NOT add \"Let There Be Blood\", which is a compilation album despite the fact that it is a re-recording of \"Bonded by Blood\". All other releases (EPs, singles, etc.) are covered in the discography article and are not to be listed in this section. See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians/Article_guidelines#Discography_section-->\n* ''[[Bonded by Blood]]'' (1985)\n* ''[[Pleasures of the Flesh]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Fabulous Disaster]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Impact Is Imminent]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[Force of Habit]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Tempo of the Damned]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Shovel Headed Kill Machine]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[The Atrocity Exhibition... Exhibit A]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Exhibit B: The Human Condition]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Blood In, Blood Out (Exodus album)|Blood In, Blood Out]]'' (2014)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Exodus (band)|Exodus}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.exodusattack.com}}\n* [http://www.myspace.com/exodus Official MySpace page]\n* [http://www.metalfan.ro/articol.php?sectiune=2&id_doc=3166&lng=2 Exodus&nbsp;\u2013 Gary Holt interview @ Metalfan.ro&nbsp;\u2013 English]\n\n{{Exodus(band)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Exodus}}\n[[Category:1979 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1979]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 1994]]\n[[Category:Musical groups reestablished in 1997]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 1998]]\n[[Category:Musical groups reestablished in 2001]]\n[[Category:Musical quintets]]\n[[Category:Nuclear Blast artists]]\n[[Category:Political music]]\n[[Category:Thrash metal musical groups from California]]\n[[Category:Combat Records artists]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records artists]]\n[[Category:Century Media Records artists]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo/fmt (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exodus_(American_band)"}
{"title_page": "Max Breunig", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name= Max Breunig\n| image = \n| fullname = \n| height = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date|df=yes|1888|11|12}} \n| birth_place = [[Karlsruhe]], [[Germany]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|df=yes|1961|7|4|1888|11|12}}\n| death_place = [[Pforzheim]], [[West Germany]]\n| position = [[Defender (football)|Defender]]/[[Midfielder (football)|Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = 1901\u20131908 \n| youthclubs1 = [[Karlsruher FV]] \n| years1 = 1908\u20131912 \n| years2 = 1912\u20131918\n| clubs1 = [[Karlsruher FV]] \n| clubs2 = [[1. FC Pforzheim]]\n| caps1 = \n| goals1 = \n| nationalyears1 = 1910\u20131913\n| nationalteam1 = [[Germany national football team|Germany]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 9  \n| nationalgoals1 = 1 \n| manageryears1 = 1921\u20131922 \n| manageryears2 = 1922\u20131923 \n| manageryears3 = 1926\u20131928 \n| manageryears4 = 1930\u20131934\n| managerclubs1 = [[Karlsruher FV]] \n| managerclubs2 = [[FC Basel]] \n| managerclubs3 = [[TSV M\u00fcnchen 1860]] \n| managerclubs4 = [[TSV M\u00fcnchen 1860]]\n}}\n\n'''Max Breunig''' (12 November 1888 near [[Karlsruhe]] \u2013 4 July 1961 in [[Pforzheim]]) was a [[German Empire|German]] amateur [[football (soccer)|football]] player who competed in the [[1912 Summer Olympics]].\n\nBreunig, a midfielder, started his career at [[Karlsruher FV]] in 1908, and on the final day of the 1909/10 German League season, he scored the winning goal (a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]]) in a 1-0 win against [[Holstein Kiel]] to win the championship. In 1913 he signed for [[1. FC Pforzheim]] but his football career ended when the [[First World War]] began.\n\nHe captained the [[Germany national football team|German national team]] in all nine games he played for them and was a member of the [[Football at the 1912 Summer Olympics|German 1912 Olympic squad]] and played one match in the main tournament. He scored one goal at international level.\n\nAfter his playing days, he became a teacher and he also went on to manage Karlsruher from 1921 until 1922, [[FC Basel]] from 1922 to 1923<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/players/trainers-zwit-clubs.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=26 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080627223859/http://www.rsssf.com/players/trainers-zwit-clubs.html |archivedate=27 June 2008 }}</ref> and [[TSV M\u00fcnchen 1860]] from 1925 until 1928 and from 1930 until 1934.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{WorldFootball.net|max-breunig}}\n* {{Fussballdaten|breunigmax}}\n\n{{Germany squad 1912 Summer Olympics}}\n{{FC Basel managers}}\n{{TSV 1860 M\u00fcnchen managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Breunig, Max}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1961 deaths]]\n[[Category:German footballers]]\n[[Category:Germany international footballers]]\n[[Category:Olympic footballers of Germany]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 1912 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:FC Basel managers]]\n[[Category:TSV 1860 Munich managers]]\n[[Category:Karlsruher FV players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Karlsruhe]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]]\n[[Category:German football managers]]\n\n\n{{Germany-footy-defender-1880s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name= Max Breunig\n| image = \n| fullname = \n| height = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1888|11|12}} \n| birth_place = [[Karlsruhe]], [[Germany]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1961|7|4|1888|11|12}}\n| death_place = [[Pforzheim]], [[West Germany]]\n| position = [[Defender (football)|Defender]]/[[Midfielder (football)|Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = 1901\u20131908 \n| youthclubs1 = [[Karlsruher FV]] \n| years1 = 1908\u20131912 \n| years2 = 1912\u20131918\n| clubs1 = [[Karlsruher FV]] \n| clubs2 = [[1. FC Pforzheim]]\n| caps1 = \n| goals1 = \n| nationalyears1 = 1910\u20131913\n| nationalteam1 = [[Germany national football team|Germany]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 9  \n| nationalgoals1 = 1 \n| manageryears1 = 1921\u20131922 \n| manageryears2 = 1922\u20131923 \n| manageryears3 = 1926\u20131928 \n| manageryears4 = 1930\u20131934\n| managerclubs1 = [[Karlsruher FV]] \n| managerclubs2 = [[FC Basel]] \n| managerclubs3 = [[TSV M\u00fcnchen 1860]] \n| managerclubs4 = [[TSV M\u00fcnchen 1860]]\n}}\n\n'''Max Breunig''' (November 12, 1888 near [[Karlsruhe]] \u2013 July 4, 1961 in [[Pforzheim]]) was a [[German Empire|German]] amateur [[football (soccer)|football]] player who competed in the [[1912 Summer Olympics]].\n\nBreunig, a midfielder, started his career at [[Karlsruher FV]] in 1908, and on the final day of the 1909/10 German League season, he scored the winning goal (a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]]) in a 1-0 win against [[Holstein Kiel]] to win the championship. In 1913 he signed for [[1. FC Pforzheim]] but his football career ended when the [[First World War]] began.\n\nHe captained the [[Germany national football team|German national team]] in all nine games he played for them and was a member of the [[Football at the 1912 Summer Olympics|German 1912 Olympic squad]] and played one match in the main tournament. He scored one goal at international level.\n\nAfter his playing days, he became a teacher and he also went on to manage Karlsruher from 1921 until 1922, [[FC Basel]] from 1922 to 1923<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/players/trainers-zwit-clubs.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-08-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080627223859/http://www.rsssf.com/players/trainers-zwit-clubs.html |archivedate=2008-06-27 }}</ref> and [[TSV M\u00fcnchen 1860]] from 1925 until 1928 and from 1930 until 1934.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{WorldFootball.net|max-breunig}}\n* {{Fussballdaten|breunigmax}}\n\n{{Germany squad 1912 Summer Olympics}}\n{{FC Basel managers}}\n{{TSV 1860 M\u00fcnchen managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Breunig, Max}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1961 deaths]]\n[[Category:German footballers]]\n[[Category:Germany international footballers]]\n[[Category:Olympic footballers of Germany]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 1912 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:FC Basel managers]]\n[[Category:TSV 1860 Munich managers]]\n[[Category:Karlsruher FV players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Karlsruhe]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]]\n[[Category:German football managers]]\n\n\n{{Germany-footy-defender-1880s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "S.A. Julio", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Max_Breunig"}
{"title_page": "Brent Fitz", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=September 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Brent Fitz\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image               = Brent Fitz.jpg\n| caption             = Brent Fitz performing live with Slash at Festivalna hall, Sofia, during the Apocalyptic Love World Tour 2013.\n| birth_name          = Brent Fitz\n| alias               =\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1970|3|27}}\n| birth_place         = [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]], Canada\n| death_date          =\n| genre               = [[Hard Rock]], [[Pop music|Pop]], [[Blues]]\n| occupation          = [[Musician]]\n| instrument          = [[Drum kit|Drums]], [[bass guitar]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]]<!--- If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n| years_active        = 1986 - present\n| label               =\n| associated_acts     = [[Slash (guitarist)|Slash]], [[Union (band)|Union]], [[Vince Neil]], [[Theory of a Deadman]], [[Alice Cooper]], [[Econoline Crush]], [[Gene Simmons]]\n| website             = [http://www.brentfitz.com/ www.brentfitz.com]\n}}\n\n'''Brent Fitz''' (born March 27, 1970) is a [[Canadian-American]] musician and [[multi-instrumentalist]]. In his career, he has worked with [[Slash (musician)|Slash]], [[Myles Kennedy]], [[Theory of a Deadman]], [[Alice Cooper]], [[Vince Neil]], [[Union (band)|Union]], [[Gene Simmons]], [[The Guess Who]], [[Brad Whitford]] from [[Aerosmith]], [[Derek St. Holmes]], [[Ronnie Montrose]], [[Indigenous (band)|Indigenous]], [[Lamya]], [[Streetheart (band)|Streetheart]], [[Harlequin (band)|Harlequin]], and [[Econoline Crush]].\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Early life ===\n\nBrent is a native of [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]], Canada where he grew up with his parents Mervyn and Audrey Fitz and a sister, Brenda, who is also a professional musician.<ref>[http://passages.winnipegfreepress.com/passage-details/id-74610/name-Helen_Fitz/ Helen Fitz] (grandmother) obituary, published in the Winnipeg Free Press, January 2, 2003.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/brenda_fitz|title=Brenda Fitz (@Brenda_Fitz) {{!}} Twitter|website=twitter.com|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref> He attended and graduated from [[John Taylor Collegiate]] in 1988.<ref name=\":2\" /> His parents continue to take a keen interest in his career, with his mother Audrey cited as saying \"we get to look at his tour schedule and follow him across the world\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/local/rock-drummer-rolls-back-into-winnipeg-163149086.html|title = Rock drummer rolls back into Winnipeg|date = July 20, 2012|accessdate = October 6, 2014|website = Winnipeg Free Press|publisher = |last = Scurfield|first = Maureen}}</ref> After leaving Winnipeg in the mid 1990s, he lived for some time in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]] and currently resides in [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]], as does his sister.<ref name=\":1\">Brenda Fitz LinkedIn [https://www.linkedin.com/in/brenda-fitz-5aa3a17 entry].</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.52peakclub.com/brenda-fitz.html|title=Brenda Fitz|website=52 Peak Club|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\nFitz started piano lessons at the age of five and drums at the age of ten, playing percussion in his middle school and high school jazz and concert band music programs. He received piano and theory training through [[Royal Conservatory of Music (Toronto)|The Royal Conservatory of Music]] in [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]] and graduated in 1994.<ref name=\":2\">Resume on [https://www.linkedin.com/pub/brent-fitz/9/a17/741 Linkedin].</ref> In 1985, Brent answered an ad for a teaching job at a local drum shop in Winnipeg, and despite being only 15 at the time, was hired based on his excelled musical ability and people skills.\n\n==== Move to LA ====\nFitz got his professional start at age 15, playing in various Winnipeg clubs and outlying areas in a cover band named New Alliance. After graduating high school, he formed the band Seventh Heaven with two local musicians and two Los Angeles natives that had recently relocated to Winnipeg.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.maidenfans.com/index.php?ACT=module&name=rwnews&area=article&nid=1845|title=Maidenfans.com \u2013 Interview with Chris Jericho}}</ref> After several years of touring, Brent formed another band with Seventh Heaven's guitarist, which evolved into Shake Naked.<ref name=\"members.ozemail.com.au\">{{cite news|url= http://members.ozemail.com.au/~cruekiss/97.htm\n|title=Paul Miles \u2013 Chronologically Crue}}</ref> Of this period, his father related that 'we used to go to every gig he played in Winnipeg bars, ladies of the night would pass us, going through to go to the bathroom\".<ref name=\":0\" /> Schedules with Seventh Heaven and Shake Naked were much more extensive and involved touring most of [[Canada]]. In 1993, Fitz joined Kenny Shields from the band [[Streetheart (band)|Streetheart]] and toured across Canada for the next three years. In 1996, while attending the NAMM music trade show in Anaheim, California, connections to the city of [[Los Angeles]] within the band Seventh Heaven, allowed Fitz to have the opportunity to seek work in that market as a performer and session player.<ref name=\"members.ozemail.com.au\" />\n\nWorking with previous Shake Naked vocalist Lenita Erickson later proved fruitful as Erickson's friend [[Bruce Kulick]] of [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]] fame invited Fitz to join him in a recording effort after first hearing him play piano, and later seeing him play drums at The Roxy in Hollywood, with former [[Duran Duran]] singer, [[Lamya]] .<ref name=\"members.ozemail.com.au\" /> That band would become known as [[Union (band)|Union]]<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://hometown.aol.com/kissunderground2/brentfitzinterview.html\n|title=kissunderground \u2013 Interview with Brent Fitz\n|access-date=2008-02-27\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050310142601/http://hometown.aol.com/kissunderground2/brentfitzinterview.html\n|archive-date=2005-03-10\n|url-status=dead\n}}</ref> and would also include [[John Corabi]] on vocals (formerly of [[The Scream (band)|The Scream]] and [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]]), [[James Hunting]] of [[David Lee Roth]] on bass, with Kulick on guitar. This four-piece released their self-titled debut in 1998.<ref>Discogs.com [http://www.discogs.com/Union-Union/release/3233499 listing] of the (re-)release with credits.</ref> A live record titled \"Live In The Galaxy\" was released in 1999, and the band recorded a second album titled \"The Blue Room\" that was released in February, 2000.\n\n==== Vince Neil ====\nIn September 2000, Fitz briefly joined the [[Bulletboys]] on tour in support of their Best Of collection,<ref>[http://www.rockdetector.com/artist/united+states/california/los+angeles/bulletboys Listing] and overview of members and former members of the band.</ref> and recorded several new songs at Cherokee Studios in Los Angeles with famed Led Zeppelin producer, Andy Johns. Soon after, he also toured and recorded with [[Gilby Clarke]], and recorded drum tracks for the Slimmer Twins album Lack Of Luxury, featuring Kix guitarist Ronnie Younkins.<ref>The Slimmer Twin [http://slimmertwins.com/bio.html bio] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110827105522/http://slimmertwins.com/bio.html |date=August 27, 2011 }}, indicating he played on their album Lack of Luxury (2000).</ref><ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Gilby-Clarke-Swag/release/1826915 Credited] on the song 'Warm Country Sun' featured on the Gilby Clarke album ''Swag'' (March 2002).</ref> In early 2001, Fitz received an invitation to tour with [[Vince Neil]] who re-released his two solo-records that summer.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://idobi.com/news/2001/05/motley-crues-vince-neil-to-reissue-two-albums-on-beyond-musicvns-records/|title = Motley Crue's Vince Neil to Re-issue two albums on Beyond Music/VNS Records|date = May 14, 2001|accessdate = October 5, 2014|website = idobi.com|publisher = |last = Fiasco|first = Lance}}</ref> Performing on several international tours, and recorded the album \"Live At The Whisky\" in 2002.<ref>Allmusic.com listing of the [http://www.discogs.com/Gilby-Clarke-Swag/release/1826915 album].</ref> In the same year he joined Neil for the [[Rock Never Stops Tour|Rock Never Stops]] Tour from may through to July,<ref>Tourdates [http://www.knac.com/article.asp?ArticleID=745 listing] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006223723/http://www.knac.com/article.asp?ArticleID=745 |date=October 6, 2014 }} with (promo) details on KNAC.com.</ref> followed by a support slot for [[Poison (American band)|Poison]] in 2003.<ref>Blabbermouth.net [http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/poison-vince-neil-skid-row-first-tour-dates-announced/ news item] from March 5, 2003.</ref> He continued to feature with Neil on tour, although the imminent M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce reunion at the end of 2004 put the band on hiatus.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.mtv.com/news/1480624/motley-crue-reuniting-for-tour-possible-lp-tommy-vince-have-yet-to-speak/|title = Motley Crue Reuniting For Tour, Possible LP; Tommy, Vince Have Yet To Speak.|date = November 24, 2003|accessdate = October 5, 2014|website = MTV.com|publisher = Viacom|last = Kaufman|first = Gil}}</ref>\n\n==== Alice Cooper ====\nIn the first half of 2005 Fitz joined the Canadian band [[Theory of a Deadman]] as the band embarked on tour to support the album \"Gasoline\".<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.billboard.com/artist/419497/theory-deadman/biography|title = Theory of a Deadman: Biography|date = 2012|accessdate = October 7, 2014|website = Billboard.com|publisher = Rovi|last = Rivadavia|first = Eduardo}}</ref> The band had fired their original drummer Tim Hart, while Robin Diaz played the parts on the album. According to guitarist David Brenner, Fitz is 'a music theory nut' who also contributed backing vocals and piano. He was 'able to come in and play these other guys' parts and really make them his own'.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/interviews/interviews/theory_of_a_deadman_rock_n_roll_quality.html|title = Theory Of A Deadman: Rock N' Roll Quality|date = September 28, 2006|accessdate = October 7, 2014|website = Ultimate-Guitar.com|publisher = |last = Rosen|first = Steven}}</ref> Fitz appeared in four music videos with the band, and made several TV appearances including [[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]].\n\nIn July 2006, while still touring with Theory of a Deadman, Fitz temporarily left the band to tour with [[Alice Cooper]], filling in on drums for [[Eric Singer]] while Singer was touring with [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]].<ref>Blabbermouth.net News [http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/drummer-brent-fitz-to-play-more-dates-with-alice-cooper/ item].</ref> Later that year, Fitz toured the US with Mato Nanji as [[Indigenous (band)|Indigenous]] in support of the album ''Chasing the Sun''.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://articles.mcall.com/2006-10-12/entertainment/3706047_1_emo-bands-alkaline-trio/2|title = Waidestock! is hip deep in punk, emo and rock bands (p. 2)|date = October 12, 2006|accessdate = October 7, 2014|website = The Morning Call|publisher = |last = Righi|first = Len}}</ref> He also took part in the sessions for the [[Harlequin (band)|Harlequin]] album'' Waking the Jester'' released in 2007.<ref>Allmusic.com [http://www.allmusic.com/album/waking-the-jester-mw0001104442/credits credits] for the album.</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Fitz recorded with the recently reformed Canadian rock act [[Econoline Crush]] on the album ''[[Ignite (Econoline Crush album)|Ignite]]''.<ref>Allmusic.com [http://www.allmusic.com/album/ignite-mw0001641221/credits credits] for the Ignite album.</ref> He subsequently became a permanent member of the band, while still remaining as regular back-up drummer with [[Alice Cooper]].<ref>Bravewords.com news-item on his participation in the Australian tour. Dates May 13, 2007.</ref> Fitz appeared in the video for the Econoline Crush hit song \"Dirty\".\n\n==== Bruce Kulick ====\nIn 2009, Fitz joined the Las Vegas-based production of 'Monster Circus' as keyboardist/guitarist/vocalist. Monster Circus performed at The Hilton Hotel and Casino in [[Las Vegas Strip|Las Vegas]], Nevada. The band featured [[Dee Snider]] of [[Twisted Sister]], bassist [[Rudy Sarzo]], guitarist Tony Montana of [[Great White (band)|Great White]], guitarist [[Dave Kushner]] from [[Velvet Revolver]], and [[John Corabi]] and [[Bruce Kulick]] (from Fitz's former band Union).\n\nIn June 2009, Fitz appeared on the television show [[Gene Simmons Family Jewels]] (season 4, episode 2: Memphis Blues); he and [[Bruce Kulick]] helped with some recording studio work [[Gene Simmons]] arranged for his son [[Nick Simmons|Nick's]] musical aspirations. Fitz also recorded drums for most of the tracks on Kulick's 2010 album release ''BK3'', including tracks featuring guest artists [[Gene Simmons]], Nick Simmons, [[John Corabi]], and [[Doug Fieger]] of [[The Knack]]. Fitz appeared on a second episode in June 2010, this time performing live with Bruce Kulick and Nick Simmons at The Cat Club in Hollywood, California.\n\n==== Slash ====\nIn March 2010, Fitz became drummer for then-former [[Guns N' Roses]]/[[Velvet Revolver]] guitarist [[Slash (musician)|Slash]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.musicradar.com/rhythm/brent-fitz-talks-slash-grohl-freese-and-more-260744|title = Brent Fitz talks Slash, Grohl, Freese and more|date = July 9, 2010|accessdate = October 5, 2014|website = Musicradar.com|publisher = |last = Chamberlain|first = Rich}}</ref> The band which also features [[Alter Bridge]] singer [[Myles Kennedy]], eventually became known as Slash Featuring Myles Kennedy and The Conspirators, and released three albums: 'Apocalyptic Love' in 2012, 'World on Fire' in 2014 and 'Living The Dream' in 2018. Two live albums have been recorded also, 'Made in Stoke' 2011, and 'Live at The Roxy' in 2015. With the band, Fitz has performed on several US talk shows in including: The Tonight Show with Jay Leno, Jimmy Fallon, Jimmy Kimmel, Ellen, Conan (twice), Lopez Tonight (twice) and The Late Late Show with Craig Ferguson, as well as performed live on Howard Stern. Fitz also appeared in several music videos including 'By The Sword', 'Back From Cali', 'Beautiful Dangerous' featuring [[Fergie (singer)|Fergie]], 'You're A Lie', 'Bad Rain' and 'Anastasia'. The band has two #1 singles on the US Active Rock charts: 'You're A Lie', and 'World on Fire', as well as two top 5 songs: 'Standing In The Sun' and 'Bent to Fly' (which spent over 27 weeks on the chart). The band headlined the 2014 MTV Euro Awards in Glasgow, Scotland, playing 'Crazy Train', with a tribute to [[Ozzy Osbourne]], who received the lifetime achievement award from MTV.\n\n== Albums ==\n* Phil X & The Drills - Stupid Good Lookings, Vol.1 (2019)\n* [[Slash (musician)|Slash]] featuring Myles Kennedy & The Conspirators - Living The Dream (2018)\n* [[The Guess Who]] - The Future IS What It Used To Be (2018)\n* [[Sass Jordan]] - Racine Revisited (2017)\n* Chemia - Let Me (2015)\n* [[Slash (musician)|Slash]] featuring Myles Kennedy & The Conspirators - [[Live at the Roxy 9.25.14]] (2015)\n* [[Slash (musician)|Slash]] featuring Myles Kennedy & The Conspirators - [[World on Fire (album)|World On Fire]] (2014)\n* [[Jake E. Lee]] (Red Dragon Cartel) - Red Dragon Cartel (2014)\n* [[Slash (musician)|Slash]] featuring Myles Kennedy & The Conspirators - [[Apocalyptic Love]] (2012)\n* [[Slash (musician)|Slash]] featuring Myles Kennedy - ''[[Made in Stoke 24/7/11]]'' (2011)\n* [[Beggars & Thieves]] - ''We Are The Broken Hearted'' (2011)\n* Syndicate - Syndicate (2011)\n* [[Slash (musician)|Slash]] - [[Live in Manchester (Slash album)]] (2010)\n* [[Slash (musician)|Slash]] - ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20111223171515/http://itunes.apple.com/us/album/itunes-session-feat.-myles/id408028275 iTunes Session]'' (2010)\n* [[Slash (musician)|Slash]] - ''[[Slash (album)|Slash]]'' (Deluxe Edition) (2010)\n* [[Bruce Kulick]] - ''[[BK3 (album)|BK3]]'' (2010)\n* [[Econoline Crush]] - ''[[Ignite (Econoline Crush album)|Ignite]]'' (2008)\n* [[Harlequin (band)|Harlequin]] - ''Waking the Jester'' (2007)\n* Various Artists: ''[[WWE Wreckless Intent]]'' (2006)\n* [[Theory of a Deadman]] - ''[[Gasoline (Theory of a Deadman album)|Gasoline]] (2005)\n* [https://www.amazon.com/Numbers-From-The-Beast-All-Star/dp/B000B6TR20/ Various Artists: ''Numbers from the Beast'', a tribute to Iron Maiden] (2005)\n* [http://www.karlcochran.com/ Voodooland] - ''[https://www.amazon.ca/dp/B00083G3F0 Give Me Air]'' (2003)\n* [[Vince Neil]] - ''[[Live at the Whisky: One Night Only]]'' (2003)\n* [[Bruce Kulick]] - [[Transformer (Bruce Kulick album)|Transformer]] (2002)\n* [[Gilby Clarke]] - ''[[Swag (Gilby Clarke album)|Swag]]'' (2002)\n* [[Bruce Kulick]] - ''[[Audiodog]]'' (2001)\n* [[Union (band)|Union]] - [[The Blue Room (album)|The Blue Room]] (2000)\n* [[Union (band)|Union]] - ''Live in the Galaxy'' (1999)\n* [[Union (band)|Union]] - ''Union'' (1998)\n* [https://www.amazon.com/Forever-Mod-Portrait-Of-Storyteller/dp/B0000067Y9 Various Artists: ''Forever Mod - A Portrait of a Storyteller'', a tribute to Rod Stewart] (1998)\n* [http://www.kiss-related-recordings.nl/tribute_returncomet.html Various Artists: ''Return of the Comet'', a tribute to Ace Frehley] (1997)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Brent Fitz}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.brentfitz.com}}\n* {{IMDb name|nm1924661|Brent Fitz}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0D5750_WleA YouTube] - Brent Fitz with [[Vince Neil]] - \"Wildside\" live from Winnipeg 2003 solo tour w/[[Poison (American band)|Poison]].\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g-03noPYkWM YouTube] TV interview on The Rush in Vancouver, BC.\n\n{{Slash (musician)|Slash}}\n{{Union (band)}}\n{{Vince Neil}}\n{{Econoline Crush}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fitz, Brent}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Alternative rock drummers]]\n[[Category:Canadian alternative rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Canadian rock drummers]]\n[[Category:Canadian male drummers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Las Vegas]]\n[[Category:The Royal Conservatory of Music alumni]]\n[[Category:Vince Neil Band members]]\n[[Category:BulletBoys members]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian drummers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=September 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Brent Fitz\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image               = Brent Fitz.jpg\n| caption             = Brent Fitz performing live with Slash at Festivalna hall, Sofia, during the Apocalyptic Love World Tour 2013.\n| birth_name          = Brent Fitz\n| alias               =\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1970|3|27}}\n| birth_place         = [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]], Canada\n| death_date          =\n| genre               = [[Hard Rock]], [[Pop music|Pop]], [[Blues]]\n| occupation          = [[Musician]]\n| instrument          = [[Drum kit|Drums]], [[bass guitar]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]]<!--- If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n| years_active        = 1986 - present\n| label               =\n| associated_acts     = [[Slash (guitarist)|Slash]], [[Union (band)|Union]], [[Vince Neil]], [[Theory of a Deadman]], [[Alice Cooper]], [[Econoline Crush]], [[Gene Simmons]]\n| website             = [http://www.brentfitz.com/ www.brentfitz.com]\n}}\n\n'''Brent Fitz''' (born March 27, 1970) is a [[Canadian-American]] musician and [[multi-instrumentalist]]. In his career, he has worked with [[Slash (musician)|Slash]], [[Myles Kennedy]], [[Theory of a Deadman]], [[Alice Cooper]], [[Vince Neil]], [[Union (band)|Union]], [[Gene Simmons]], [[The Guess Who]], [[Brad Whitford]] from [[Aerosmith]], [[Derek St. Holmes]], [[Ronnie Montrose]], [[Indigenous (band)|Indigenous]], [[Lamya]], [[Streetheart (band)|Streetheart]], [[Harlequin (band)|Harlequin]], and [[Econoline Crush]].\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Early life ===\n\nBrent is a native of [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]], Canada where he grew up with his parents Mervyn and Audrey Fitz and a sister, Brenda, who is also a professional musician.<ref>[http://passages.winnipegfreepress.com/passage-details/id-74610/name-Helen_Fitz/ Helen Fitz] (grandmother) obituary, published in the Winnipeg Free Press, January 2, 2003.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/brenda_fitz|title=Brenda Fitz (@Brenda_Fitz) {{!}} Twitter|website=twitter.com|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref> He attended and graduated from [[John Taylor Collegiate]] in 1988.<ref name=\":2\" /> His parents continue to take a keen interest in his career, with his mother Audrey cited as saying \"we get to look at his tour schedule and follow him across the world\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/local/rock-drummer-rolls-back-into-winnipeg-163149086.html|title = Rock drummer rolls back into Winnipeg|date = July 20, 2012|accessdate = October 6, 2014|website = Winnipeg Free Press|publisher = |last = Scurfield|first = Maureen}}</ref> After leaving Winnipeg in the mid 90's, he lived for some time in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]] and currently resides in [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]], as does his sister.<ref name=\":1\">Brenda Fitz LinkedIn [https://www.linkedin.com/in/brenda-fitz-5aa3a17 entry].</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.52peakclub.com/brenda-fitz.html|title=Brenda Fitz|website=52 Peak Club|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\nFitz started piano lessons at the age of five and drums at the age of ten, playing percussion in his middle school and high school jazz and concert band music programs. He received piano and theory training through [[Royal Conservatory of Music (Toronto)|The Royal Conservatory of Music]] in [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]] and graduated in 1994.<ref name=\":2\">Resume on [https://www.linkedin.com/pub/brent-fitz/9/a17/741 Linkedin].</ref> In 1985, Brent answered an ad for a teaching job at a local drum shop in Winnipeg, and despite being only 15 at the time, was hired based on his excelled musical ability and people skills.\n\n==== Move to LA ====\nFitz got his professional start at age 15, playing in various Winnipeg clubs and outlying areas in a cover band named New Alliance. After graduating high school, he formed the band Seventh Heaven with two local musicians and two Los Angeles natives that had recently relocated to Winnipeg.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.maidenfans.com/index.php?ACT=module&name=rwnews&area=article&nid=1845|title=Maidenfans.com \u2013 Interview with Chris Jericho}}</ref> After several years of touring, Brent formed another band with Seventh Heaven's guitarist, which evolved into Shake Naked.<ref name=\"members.ozemail.com.au\">{{cite news|url= http://members.ozemail.com.au/~cruekiss/97.htm\n|title=Paul Miles \u2013 Chronologically Crue}}</ref> Of this period, his father related that 'we used to go to every gig he played in Winnipeg bars, ladies of the night would pass us, going through to go to the bathroom\".<ref name=\":0\" /> Schedules with Seventh Heaven and Shake Naked were much more extensive and involved touring most of [[Canada]]. In 1993, Fitz joined Kenny Shields from the band [[Streetheart (band)|Streetheart]] and toured across Canada for the next three years. In 1996, while attending the NAMM music trade show in Anaheim, California, connections to the city of [[Los Angeles]] within the band Seventh Heaven, allowed Fitz to have the opportunity to seek work in that market as a performer and session player.<ref name=\"members.ozemail.com.au\" />\n\nWorking with previous Shake Naked vocalist Lenita Erickson later proved fruitful as Erickson's friend [[Bruce Kulick]] of [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]] fame invited Fitz to join him in a recording effort after first hearing him play piano, and later seeing him play drums at The Roxy in Hollywood, with former [[Duran Duran]] singer, [[Lamya]] .<ref name=\"members.ozemail.com.au\" /> That band would become known as [[Union (band)|Union]]<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://hometown.aol.com/kissunderground2/brentfitzinterview.html\n|title=kissunderground \u2013 Interview with Brent Fitz\n|access-date=2008-02-27\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050310142601/http://hometown.aol.com/kissunderground2/brentfitzinterview.html\n|archive-date=2005-03-10\n|url-status=dead\n}}</ref> and would also include [[John Corabi]] on vocals (formerly of [[The Scream (band)|The Scream]] and [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]]), [[James Hunting]] of [[David Lee Roth]] on bass, with Kulick on guitar. This four-piece released their self-titled debut in 1998.<ref>Discogs.com [http://www.discogs.com/Union-Union/release/3233499 listing] of the (re-)release with credits.</ref> A live record titled \"Live In The Galaxy\" was released in 1999, and the band recorded a second album titled \"The Blue Room\" that was released in February, 2000.\n\n==== Vince Neil ====\nIn September 2000, Fitz briefly joined the [[Bulletboys]] on tour in support of their Best Of collection,<ref>[http://www.rockdetector.com/artist/united+states/california/los+angeles/bulletboys Listing] and overview of members and former members of the band.</ref> and recorded several new songs at Cherokee Studios in Los Angeles with famed Led Zeppelin producer, Andy Johns. Soon after, he also toured and recorded with [[Gilby Clarke]], and recorded drum tracks for the Slimmer Twins album Lack Of Luxury, featuring Kix guitarist Ronnie Younkins.<ref>The Slimmer Twin [http://slimmertwins.com/bio.html bio] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110827105522/http://slimmertwins.com/bio.html |date=August 27, 2011 }}, indicating he played on their album Lack of Luxury (2000).</ref><ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Gilby-Clarke-Swag/release/1826915 Credited] on the song 'Warm Country Sun' featured on the Gilby Clarke album ''Swag'' (March 2002).</ref> In early 2001, Fitz received an invitation to tour with [[Vince Neil]] who re-released his two solo-records that summer.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://idobi.com/news/2001/05/motley-crues-vince-neil-to-reissue-two-albums-on-beyond-musicvns-records/|title = Motley Crue's Vince Neil to Re-issue two albums on Beyond Music/VNS Records|date = May 14, 2001|accessdate = October 5, 2014|website = idobi.com|publisher = |last = Fiasco|first = Lance}}</ref> Performing on several international tours, and recorded the album \"Live At The Whisky\" in 2002.<ref>Allmusic.com listing of the [http://www.discogs.com/Gilby-Clarke-Swag/release/1826915 album].</ref> In the same year he joined Neil for the [[Rock Never Stops Tour|Rock Never Stops]] Tour from may through to July,<ref>Tourdates [http://www.knac.com/article.asp?ArticleID=745 listing] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006223723/http://www.knac.com/article.asp?ArticleID=745 |date=October 6, 2014 }} with (promo) details on KNAC.com.</ref> followed by a support slot for [[Poison (American band)|Poison]] in 2003.<ref>Blabbermouth.net [http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/poison-vince-neil-skid-row-first-tour-dates-announced/ news item] from March 5, 2003.</ref> He continued to feature with Neil on tour, although the imminent M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce reunion at the end of 2004 put the band on hiatus.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.mtv.com/news/1480624/motley-crue-reuniting-for-tour-possible-lp-tommy-vince-have-yet-to-speak/|title = Motley Crue Reuniting For Tour, Possible LP; Tommy, Vince Have Yet To Speak.|date = November 24, 2003|accessdate = October 5, 2014|website = MTV.com|publisher = Viacom|last = Kaufman|first = Gil}}</ref>\n\n==== Alice Cooper ====\nIn the first half of 2005 Fitz joined the Canadian band [[Theory of a Deadman]] as the band embarked on tour to support the album \"Gasoline\".<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.billboard.com/artist/419497/theory-deadman/biography|title = Theory of a Deadman: Biography|date = 2012|accessdate = October 7, 2014|website = Billboard.com|publisher = Rovi|last = Rivadavia|first = Eduardo}}</ref> The band had fired their original drummer Tim Hart, while Robin Diaz played the parts on the album. According to guitarist David Brenner, Fitz is 'a music theory nut' who also contributed backing vocals and piano. He was 'able to come in and play these other guys' parts and really make them his own'.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/interviews/interviews/theory_of_a_deadman_rock_n_roll_quality.html|title = Theory Of A Deadman: Rock N' Roll Quality|date = September 28, 2006|accessdate = October 7, 2014|website = Ultimate-Guitar.com|publisher = |last = Rosen|first = Steven}}</ref> Fitz appeared in four music videos with the band, and made several TV appearances including [[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]].\n\nIn July 2006, while still touring with Theory of a Deadman, Fitz temporarily left the band to tour with [[Alice Cooper]], filling in on drums for [[Eric Singer]] while Singer was touring with [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]].<ref>Blabbermouth.net News [http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/drummer-brent-fitz-to-play-more-dates-with-alice-cooper/ item].</ref> Later that year, Fitz toured the US with Mato Nanji as [[Indigenous (band)|Indigenous]] in support of the album ''Chasing the Sun''.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://articles.mcall.com/2006-10-12/entertainment/3706047_1_emo-bands-alkaline-trio/2|title = Waidestock! is hip deep in punk, emo and rock bands (p. 2)|date = October 12, 2006|accessdate = October 7, 2014|website = The Morning Call|publisher = |last = Righi|first = Len}}</ref> He also took part in the sessions for the [[Harlequin (band)|Harlequin]] album'' Waking the Jester'' released in 2007.<ref>Allmusic.com [http://www.allmusic.com/album/waking-the-jester-mw0001104442/credits credits] for the album.</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Fitz recorded with the recently reformed Canadian rock act [[Econoline Crush]] on the album ''[[Ignite (Econoline Crush album)|Ignite]]''.<ref>Allmusic.com [http://www.allmusic.com/album/ignite-mw0001641221/credits credits] for the Ignite album.</ref> He subsequently became a permanent member of the band, while still remaining as regular back-up drummer with [[Alice Cooper]].<ref>Bravewords.com news-item on his participation in the Australian tour. Dates May 13, 2007.</ref> Fitz appeared in the video for the Econoline Crush hit song \"Dirty\".\n\n==== Bruce Kulick ====\nIn 2009, Fitz joined the Las Vegas-based production of 'Monster Circus' as keyboardist/guitarist/vocalist. Monster Circus performed at The Hilton Hotel and Casino in [[Las Vegas Strip|Las Vegas]], Nevada. The band featured [[Dee Snider]] of [[Twisted Sister]], bassist [[Rudy Sarzo]], guitarist Tony Montana of [[Great White (band)|Great White]], guitarist [[Dave Kushner]] from [[Velvet Revolver]], and [[John Corabi]] and [[Bruce Kulick]] (from Fitz's former band Union).\n\nIn June 2009, Fitz appeared on the television show [[Gene Simmons Family Jewels]] (season 4, episode 2: Memphis Blues); he and [[Bruce Kulick]] helped with some recording studio work [[Gene Simmons]] arranged for his son [[Nick Simmons|Nick's]] musical aspirations. Fitz also recorded drums for most of the tracks on Kulick's 2010 album release ''BK3'', including tracks featuring guest artists [[Gene Simmons]], Nick Simmons, [[John Corabi]], and [[Doug Fieger]] of [[The Knack]]. Fitz appeared on a second episode in June 2010, this time performing live with Bruce Kulick and Nick Simmons at The Cat Club in Hollywood, California.\n\n==== Slash ====\nIn March 2010, Fitz became drummer for then-former [[Guns N' Roses]]/[[Velvet Revolver]] guitarist [[Slash (musician)|Slash]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.musicradar.com/rhythm/brent-fitz-talks-slash-grohl-freese-and-more-260744|title = Brent Fitz talks Slash, Grohl, Freese and more|date = July 9, 2010|accessdate = October 5, 2014|website = Musicradar.com|publisher = |last = Chamberlain|first = Rich}}</ref> The band which also features [[Alter Bridge]] singer [[Myles Kennedy]], eventually became known as Slash Featuring Myles Kennedy and The Conspirators, and released three albums: 'Apocalyptic Love' in 2012, 'World on Fire' in 2014 and 'Living The Dream' in 2018. Two live albums have been recorded also, 'Made in Stoke' 2011, and 'Live at The Roxy' in 2015. With the band, Fitz has performed on several US talk shows in including: The Tonight Show with Jay Leno, Jimmy Fallon, Jimmy Kimmel, Ellen, Conan (twice), Lopez Tonight (twice) and The Late Late Show with Craig Ferguson, as well as performed live on Howard Stern. Fitz also appeared in several music videos including 'By The Sword', 'Back From Cali', 'Beautiful Dangerous' featuring [[Fergie (singer)|Fergie]], 'You're A Lie', 'Bad Rain' and 'Anastasia'. The band has two #1 singles on the US Active Rock charts: 'You're A Lie', and 'World on Fire', as well as two top 5 songs: 'Standing In The Sun' and 'Bent to Fly' (which spent over 27 weeks on the chart). The band headlined the 2014 MTV Euro Awards in Glasgow, Scotland, playing 'Crazy Train', with a tribute to [[Ozzy Osbourne]], who received the lifetime achievement award from MTV.\n\n== Albums ==\n* Phil X & The Drills - Stupid Good Lookings, Vol.1 (2019)\n* [[Slash (musician)|Slash]] featuring Myles Kennedy & The Conspirators - Living The Dream (2018)\n* [[The Guess Who]] - The Future IS What It Used To Be (2018)\n* [[Sass Jordan]] - Racine Revisited (2017)\n* Chemia - Let Me (2015)\n* [[Slash (musician)|Slash]] featuring Myles Kennedy & The Conspirators - [[Live at the Roxy 9.25.14]] (2015)\n